<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 42 Bangladeshi Fishermen Feared Dead Following High Tide in Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- At least 42 fishermen were still
missing and feared dead as seven fishing boats sank in the bay on
Wednesday following rain storm and high tide in the Bay of Bengal,
official sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kabir Ahmed Sowdagar, president of the Cox's Bazar Fishing
Boat Owners Association told newsmen that seven boats sank on
Wednesday in the Bay near Cox's Bazar, about 420 kilometers
southeast of Dhaka, and several other boats could not still return
from the sea.
</P>
<P>
"Twenty-two fishermen of seven boats were still missing. There
were 20 more fishermen in the boats that were in the deep sea,"
said Kabir.
</P>
<P>
One boy was killed, two people were injured in a mud slide and
more than 15,000 were evacuated after an unusually high tide and
rain battered Islands and coastal areas, Disaster Management
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The tidal surge swept a seven-year-old boy away in Cox's Bazar
district, where officials said about 100,000 people were marooned.
</P>
<P>
More than 15,000 people were evacuated from their flooded homes
in Sandwip Island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
