<BODY>
<HEADLINE> October 23 Sets as Deadline for Bids to Host WADA Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The newly-established World Anti-
Doping Agency (WADA) has set October 23 as the deadline for the
return of the bids so the body could select the site in time to
start its operations January 2002, WADA said in a press release
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Until that time, WADA will continue working out of its
temporary offices in the Lausanne-based International Olympic
Committee (IOC).
</P>
<P>
Following the site selection procedure determined earlier this
year, WADA distributed the bidding documents related to hosting
its headquarters to all National Olympic Committees (NOCs) and
their related sports ministries on August 29.
</P>
<P>
The NOCs and sports ministries have until October 23 to submit
their bids to host WADA's permanent headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, WADA said that it signed agreements last week with
the last two International Olympic Summer Sports Federations (IFs)
that had yet to sign, the International Gymnastics Federation (FIG)
and the International Volleyball Federation (FIVB). This means
WADA is now conducting doping controls in all 28 Olympic Summer
sports prior to the opening of the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
WADA is on schedule to conduct more than 2,000 unannounced, out-
of-competition doping control tests before the 2000 Olympic Games
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
"The International Olympic Summer Sports Federations should be
congratulated for doing whatever necessary in such a short time to
clear the way for an additional, external testing program," WADA
Chairman Richard W. Pound said. "They all did so, despite the
difficulties of amending their own policies, to enhance their anti-
doping commitments and to support the clean athletes in their
sports."
</P>
<P>
"WADA and the Summer IFs have broken new ground to lay a solid
foundation for an intensified fight against doping in sport. The
continued cooperation between the Olympic Movement and the public
authorities will prove to be a formidable force on the side of the
clean, ethical athlete," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
