<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Government to Reconsider Position on Embargo Against North If Peace Talks Make Headway: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government will
consider changing its position on the embargo against the breakaway
northern area of the island if the peace talks make headway and a
final Cyprus solution emerges, government spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Michalis Papapetrou said
the
economic embargo against the illegal Turkish Cypriot regime has an
international dimension as international organizations do not
accept certificates of export issued by the northern regime.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman's comments came after Turkish Cypriot businessmen
asked Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides to lift restrictions on
imports and exports from the north.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government has declared all ports in northern Cyprus
as illegal ports of entry.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots in northern Cyprus unilaterally declared in
1983 a breakaway state recognized only by Ankara, against the
internationally acknowledged Republic of Cyprus dominated by the
Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
"The government cannot under any circumstances and does not
intend to change its position on this matter as this would be
tantamount to recognition, albeit indirect or direct, of the self-
styled Turkish Cypriot regime," Papapetrou said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would only consent to reconsider its
position "if the peace talks move ahead in a substantive manner and
we see a solution emerging on the basis of U.N. decisions,
providing for a bicommunal, bizonal federation."
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks have been held
between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides and a fourth round is
scheduled to start on September 12 in New York, aiming at paving
the way for substantive negotiations leading to a comprehensive
settlement in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"We would wish to see the Turkish Cypriots cooperate for a
solution
and then and only then we could reconsider our position,"
Papapetrou stressed, noting that as long as Turkey continues to
occupy part of Cyprus and moves outside U.N. decisions, there is no
chance for the government to change its policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
