<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus President Starts New York Journey for Millennium summit, Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides said Friday that many moves have been made in view of the
fourth round of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks on the Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at south coast Larnaca airport, on his departure for
New York to attend the U.N. millennium summit and the fourth round
of proximity talks between Greek and Turkish Cypriots, Clerides
said, "We do not know what the result of these moves will be."
</P>
<P>
He noted that if the other side remained intransigent, then
further
action would be decided by the National Council, advisory body to
the president, comprising parliamentary parties.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the Mediterranean island after an abortive coup
in Nicosia seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of proximity talks, separate meetings of the U.N.
with President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash,
have been held in an effort to pave the way for substantive
negotiations leading to a comprehensive settlement in Cyprus, but
failed to make any headway.
</P>
<P>
A fourth round is scheduled to start on September 12 in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the fourth round of talks, Clerides said it is
difficult to speak about prospects, adding that "if the Turkish
Cypriot side maintains the same tactics, then this dialogue will
have no result."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Denktash insists on his bid for recognition
of his pseudo-state in northern Cyprus, before he enters
negotiations to solve the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
According to local media, Clerides will stop over in London and
will proceed to new York on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He is due to meet Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis on
September 8 to discuss the strategy at the Cyprus talks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that the Americans in particular want to see
progress in the fourth round of the talks before the U.S.
presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
