<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Main Opposition Party Elects New Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Renowned jurist Noeman Gomma was
elected on Friday as president of the New Wafd Party, Egypt's main
opposition party, the country's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Gomma, who has been the party's first vice president since the
early 1990s, succeeds Fouad Seragedin, a long-time leader who died
on August 9.
</P>
<P>
He was backed by 500 of the 843 members of the party general
assembly, with Seragedin's grandson, Fouad Badrawi, assistant
secretary general of the party, taking the second place with 129
votes to lead two other candidates, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Gomma joined the party in 1952 and was a member of its committee
at the University of Cairo's law faculty, of which he eventually
became dean and from which he retired six years ago.
</P>
<P>
In a weekly column in the party's newspaper, Al-Wafd, Gomma is a
frequent critic of the government.
</P>
<P>
The original Wafd party, in power from 1919 to 1952, led the
revolt against the British protectorate in Egypt. Along with all
other parties, it was banned after the revolution that overthrew
the monarchy in 1952.
</P>
<P>
Under the name New Wafd, the party re-emerged in 1978 when the
late president, Anwar Sadat, reinstated multi-party politics. Only
four months later, the party withdrew from active politics to
protest measures Sadat imposed which it considered undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
The party returned once again to the political scene in 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
