<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Still Rejects Former Botswanan President as Mediator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic
of the Congo (DRC) Friday reaffirmed its refusal to take former
Botswanan President Ketumile Masire as mediator for the inter-
Congolese political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"Masire is incompetent. He doesn't understand the history of
the DRC," Ambassador of the DRC to Tanzania Theodore Mugalu said
at a news conference here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mugalu said language barrier is another reason that the country
refuses Masire as facilitator in the negotiations aimed at
restoring peace in Africa's third largest country.
</P>
<P>
He also accused Masire of being biased, saying that "he had
shown clearly that he was favoring Tutsis in Rwanda and he was a
member of the genocide committee. That's why we didn't accept him.
"
</P>
<P>
Masire is not the only wise man in the world to mediate in the
DRC political negotiations, said Mugalu, adding: "Since we don't
accept Masire, the only option will be to pick another facilitator.
"
</P>
<P>
During the recent second summit on the DRC held in Namibia,
heads of states from the Southern African Development Community
and Salim Ahmed Salim, secretary general of the Organization of
African Unity, had pleaded with DRC President Laurent Kabila to
accept Masire as the facilitator of the inter-Congolese political
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Fighting in the DRC broke out in August 1998 when rebels,
backed by Rwanda and Uganda, accused Kabila of corruption and
harboring Hutu militiamen who fled Rwanda after committing
genocide there in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
