<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Djibouti Port Tries Best to Become Regional Port Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DJIBOUTI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The port of Djibouti, built
in the early 1950s, is on its way to become a port giant in the
Horn of Africa after privatization, Luc Deruyver, director general
of the port said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The port of Djibouti, the biggest of its kind in the region,
has become a branch of the Dubai International Port of the United
Arab Emirates," Deruyver told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Instead of remaining an enterprise under the administration of
the Djibouti government, the Port of Djibouti is striving to meet
its commercial target, he said, adding that six senior staff
members from the Port of Dubai will involve in the management of
the Djibouti port.
</P>
<P>
According to the director general, the port aims to competing
against the Port of Sudan and the Mombassa Port of Kenya, both of
which are international class ports in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
The government of Djibouti signed early this year a contract
with the Port of Dubai authority to invite the latter to implement
commercial management over the Port of Djibouti in a bid to
promote the capacity of the port.
</P>
<P>
The contract, effective as of June 1, 2000, will last for 20
years.
</P>
<P>
To expand the handling capacity, the government of Djibouti
imported from China two 50-ton gantry cranes at a cost of 15
million U.S. dollars early this year.
</P>
<P>
The Port of Djibouti, which was constructed by the French as a
base of military supply in early years, has become an important
outlet of Ethiopia, which became a land-locked country when its
northern state of Eritrea declared independence in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Port of Djibouti became the sole outlet of Ethiopia's
import and export goods when a two-year-old border conflict
between Ethiopia and Eritrea broke out in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's cargoes currently account for more than 70 percent
of the total cargoes that the port handles, said Saad Omar Guelleh,
technical manager of the port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
