<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Quits Regional Economic Bloc </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's membership in
the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) ceased
Friday, according to a foreign ministry official.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Chokalla, director of Information, Policy and Planning
in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation,
said that the move followed the maturity of the government's one-
year notice of intention to pull out of the regional economic bloc,
which was tabled in Lusaka, Zambia one year ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Chokalla said, although Tanzania ceased to be a member
of COMESA, it would honor all its pending obligations including
payments of annual contributions which were in arrears.
</P>
<P>
He hinted that the government decided to pull out of the group
following a study conducted to find out how much Tanzania
benefited from COMESA.
</P>
<P>
Iddi Simba, minister for Industries and Trade, said early that
Tanzania decided to quit COMESA purely on economic reasons.
</P>
<P>
He said the aims of COMESA are similar to those of the East
African Community (EAC) and Southern Africa Development Community
(SADC), which Tanzania enjoys membership, therefore it is
uneconomical for its government to pay annual fees totaling tens
of millions of Tanzanian shillings.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania had not benefited from the COMESA trade arrangements
with other member states whose economies were stronger, explained
Simba, adding that Tanzania's exports to COMESA member states had
been considerably low over the years.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, which was formed in 1994 to replace the Preferential
Trade Area (PTA), together with the EAC and SADC, all aim at
strengthening the market and economic cooperation in the eastern
and southern Africa region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
