<HEADLINE> Li Peng Meets With Parliament Leaders Attending U.N. Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislator Li
Peng on Friday met respectively with the parliament leaders from
New Zealand, Italy and Brazil, who are attending the millennium
summit of parliament leaders at the United Nations headquarters in
New York.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Jonathan Hunt, speaker of the House of
Representatives of New Zealand, Li said the National People's
Congress of China attaches great importance to developing friendly
relations and cooperation with the New Zealand parliament and is
willing to increase mutual exchanges in a multi-level and multi-
channel manner.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that more New Zealand parliamentarians will visit
China to help deepen their understanding of the country and build
up mutual trust and friendship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At his meeting with Luciano Violante, president of the Chamber
of Deputies of Italy, Li Peng noted that there have been good
relations between their parliaments in the past 30 years since
China and Italy established diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
Li and Violante exchanged views on legislative work in their
respective nations and agreed to further increase exchanges
between their legislative bodies.
</P>
<P>
Violante said he was greatly impressed by the speech Li Peng
delivered on Wednesday at the opening session of the millennium
summit. He said he fully agrees with the viewpoints made by Li in
his speech.
</P>
<P>
He added that Italy and China have identical views on the issue
of reforming the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Violante, Li Peng also had a talk with
president of the Brazilian Chamber of Deputies Michael Temer. The
two leaders agreed to expand parliamentary ties to keep pace with
the development of the overall relationship between China and
Brazil. 
</P>
