<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs

from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Russian electricity distribution company, United
Energy Systems, said on Friday that it would sell electricity to
Turkey via Azerbaijan, reported the Anatolia News Agency on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The company said that an agreement which allowed exports of
electricity to Turkey via Azerbaijan had been signed.
</P>
<P>
The company did not give information about the amount of
electricity it would sell to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey and Uganda signed a technical, economic and
commercial cooperation agreement here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Turkish State Minister Hasan Gemici
and Deputy Ugandan Prime Minister Musa Ali.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the signing ceremony, Gemici said that both countries
were eager to further improve relations between the two countries
and a joint economic commission will be set up to this end.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan Deputy Prime Minister said that he would invite
Gemici to Uganda to sign the second cooperation agreement in the
near
future.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Emirates Airline Friday launched its first
flight between Dubai and Chennai (India), reported the United Arab
Emirates official news agency.
</P>
<P>
Emirates is operating an Airbus A310-300 aircraft on the new
route which provides 18 seats in first class, 25 in business and
131 in economy.
</P>
<P>
"We are delighted to be operating to a third destination in
India," said Ghaith Al Ghaith, director of Emirates' Commercial
Operations, "Chennai is a major commercial centre and the heart of
India's software development industry and we are confident that
this route will prove a great success in terms of both business and
leisure travelers and for our cargo operations."
</P>
<P>
Emirates operates flights from Dubai to Chennai on Mondays,
Wednesdays, Fridays and Saturdays, with return flights on Mondays,
Thursdays, Fridays and Sundays.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Habib Bank AG Zurich has become the first bank in
the United Arab Emirates, and possibly the Middle East, to offer
WAP-based banking services, reported the official news agency on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bank Friday rolled out a series of facilities using leading-
edge technology that can be accessed through Wireless Application
Protocol telephony.
</P>
<P>
Specific services include web-banking, e-banking, accessing ATM
Switch facilities, and GSM push banking, for both commercial and
private customers, and all accessible through WAP telephones.
</P>
<P>
The systems underlying all the new WAP-based services constitute
proprietary software, with all of it developed in-house, and all
being inter-linked.
</P>
<P>
The web-banking will enable customers to access accounts via
their mobile phones, providing such data as consolidated account
information and currency rates, and allow them to transfer funds
between accounts.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The London-based British Safety Council (BSC),
Europe's largest independent workplace safety organization designed
to promote health, safety and environment (HSE), has found its way
to energy-rich Oman, reported local media on Friday.
</P>
<P>
BSC, whose other Gulf presence is in Jebel Ali of Dubai, has
signed a deal with the Muscat-based Occupational Training
International (OTI).
</P>
<P>
The deal has coincided with the silver jubilee celebrations of
BSC, which enjoys a membership of over 12,000 in more than 50
countries.
</P>
<P>
Now the BSC has permanent operations in Abu Dhabi, Syria and
Baku in Azerbaijan. 
</P>
