<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Positive on Clinton's Decision to Delay Missile Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Russian military Friday
described as "constructive" U.S. President Bill Clinton's decision
to leave the issue of whether to deploy a national missile defense
system to the next administration.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, whose term in office expires in January next year,
announced Friday in a speech at Georgetown University that he is
letting his successor finally decide whether to deploy a national
missile defense (NMD) system.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's statement shows "constructive elements in the U.S.
administration's activity." "There is hope that a balanced
approach to the solution of salient international problems, above
all those concerning global security, will prevail," Col. Gen.
Leonid Ivashov, chief of the Russian Defense Ministry's
international military cooperation department, said here late
Friday
</P>
<P>
"I believe Russian-U.S. consultations on the U.S. national Anti-
Ballistic Missile (ABM) defense system issue will continue with U.
S. future administration at all levels," Ivashov said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's outstanding Academician Georgy Arbatov, honorary
director of Russia's Institute of the U.S. and Canada, told press
that Clinton's statement testifies to the common sense of the
outgoing U.S. administration.
</P>
<P>
Clinton "could hardly make a bolder decision, given the looming
elections," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The very fact that the U.S. president decided to be explicit
rather than keep a low profile before the upcoming presidential
elections indicates that quite strong and influential circles in
America are aware of how dangerous it is to deploy a national
missile umbrella, Arbatov said.
</P>
<P>
An ABM defense system will lead to a new spiral in the arms
race, and "ultimately bury all hopes of those living on the planet
for a safer world," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's statement "will undoubtedly have some influence on
the new administration when it deals with the ABM issue," Arbatov
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
