<HEADLINE> Somalia's New President Visits Baidoa Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Somalia's newly elected
president Abdiqasim Salad Hassan visited southern Somali town of
Baidoa on Friday after spending two days in the capital Mogadishu
on a tour aimed at showing the international community that the
new government could operate inside Somalia even though it was
established in neighboring Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
The president and his delegation including over 90 members of
the transitional parliament flew on three small planes from
Issaley airport of north Mogadishu and were received warm welcome
at the Baidoa airport by tens of thousands of cheering people
waving the Somali and Djibouti flags and green leaves and flowers.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of battle wagons with hundreds of heavily armed
militiamen escorted the delegation from the airport to the soccer
stadium where tens of thousands of people had been waiting since
early in the morning.
</P>
<P>
The president, who was greeted with the national anthem and
other patriotic songs by a local band, conveyed his deepest and
heartfelt condolences to the families of those who died or got
disabled during the civil war, and asked the Somalis to forgive
each other and put the past behind.
</P>
<P>
The president also told the rally that the reconstruction of
the country would be given a priority by his administration.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Mohamed Nur Shargudud, chairman of the Rahanwein
Resistance Army (RRA), and Abdulla Dero Issak, speaker of the
transitional national assembly and secretary-general of the RRA
also addressed the jubilant people under the fierce sun.
</P>
<P>
The RRA-controlled Baidoa was designated as the temporary
capital of the new Somali government until the tension eased in
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The delegation canceled a trip to the central town of Beletuein
for time constraints and returned to Djibouti Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The new president went home three days after he was sworn in
last Sunday (August 27) in the small Djibouti town of Arta where
the Somali peace conference elected the country's first parliament
and head of state since Somali president Mohamed Siyad Barre was
overthrown in 1991, leading to a decade of anarchy and separatist
rule of warlords. 
</P>
</TEXT>
