<HEADLINE> The Demon of Racism Still Lurks in South Africa: UN Official  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Racist laws have been
scrapped but the demon of racism still lurks in South Africa and
racially-motivated acts of violence are still apparent, UN human
rights official Nozipho January-Bardill said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"While racism has been removed from the statute books and new
laws are being passed through Parliament to protect us all from
discrimination-- racially motivated crimes still continue,"
January-Bardill told delegates at the on-going national conference
on racism held in Sandton, Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
"Acts of racial murders still continue ... black farm workers
and white farmers appear to be the most vulnerable," said January-
Bardill, who serves on the United Nations Committee on the
Elimination of Discrimination.
</P>
<P>
The South African-born official said although violence should
not be condoned, it should be seen in its socio-economic context.
</P>
<P>
As to racially motivated acts in schools, January-Bardill said,
different types of punishment meted to black and white children at
schools for misconduct clearly indicated who was valued and who
was not.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that if racism was to be overcome at schools and
on farms, social justice, democracy and economic power were the
key factors needed to be examined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
