<HEADLINE> Six EU Members Face Legal Action for Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Friday that it has decided to take six members of the European
Union to the European Court of Justice for non-respect for their
obligations under EU's Major Accident Hazards Directive.
</P>
<P>
The Commission, EU's executive arm, said that Luxembourg,
Ireland and Portugal have not adopted and communicated any
legislation to give effect to the Directive, and Germany, Belgium
and Austria have adopted and communicated incomplete legislation.
</P>
<P>
EU environment commissioner Margot Wallstrom said, "Experience
tells us we need to be pro-active in avoiding major industrial
accidents. I therefore find it disturbing that six member states
are more than a year later in fully adapting their laws to this
important directive, which has pubic safety as its central aim."
</P>
<P>
The relevant directive is aimed at preventing major accidents
involving dangerous substances and limiting their consequences to
man and the environment.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for adopting and sending the necessary national
legislation to the Commission was February 3, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive said in a statement that the decisions in
these cases are a mark of the Commission's determination to fully
establish as soon as possible the common EU framework for
preventing and limiting the consequences of major accidents
involving dangerous substance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
