<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Leaves Missile Shield Decision to His Successor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton
decided on Friday not to authorize the deployment of a
controversial national missile defense (NMD) system at present and
thus left a final decision on the issue to his successor.
</P>
<P>
"I simply cannot conclude, with the information I have today,
that we have enough confidence in the technology and the
operational effectiveness of the entire NMD system to move forward
to deployment," Clinton said in a speech at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, I have decided not to authorize deployment of a
national missile defense at this time," he stated.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, whose term will expire on January 20 next year, said
that he has asked Secretary of Defense William Cohen, who is
perhaps the administration's strongest proponent of NMD, to
continue a robust program of development and testing.
</P>
<P>
"That effort still is at an early stage. Only three of the 19
planned intercept tests have been held so far," Clinton said. "We
need more tests, against more challenging targets, and more
simulations, before we can responsibly commit our nation's
resources to deployment."
</P>
<P>
"We should use this time to ensure that NMD, if deployed, would
actually enhance our overall national security," Clinton noted.
</P>
<P>
"I have reached this decision about not deploying the NMD after
careful deliberation," he said, adding that his decision will not
have a significant impact on the date the overall system could be
deployed in the next administration if the next president decides
to go forward.
</P>
<P>
According to experts' judgment, he said, if the next president
decides to move forward next year, the system still could be ready
or operational in 2006 or 2007.
</P>
<P>
The proposed NMD, projected to cost about 60 billion U.S.
dollars, is designed to protect all U.S. states against attack by
a limited number of long-range ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
The move, which violates the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty
signed by the former Soviet Union and the United States in 1972
and poses serious threats to global arms reduction efforts, is
widely opposed both at home and abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Not Sure About Deal on Jerusalem Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak Friday admitted that he did not know at this time whether he
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat could break the deadlock on
the fate of Jerusalem for reaching a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Since the Camp David summit between Barak, Arafat and U.S.
President Bill Clinton collapsed last month, it became more and
more clear that the thorniest issue between the two sides is the
status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel claims the holy city as its "eternal and undivided
capital", while the Palestinians hope at least East Jerusalem,
which Israel occupied in the 1967 Mideast war, will be capital of
their future state.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering of pro-peace lobbyists' movements in Tel
Aviv, Barak stressed that if a deal is finally reached, he is sure
that the city of Jerusalem will be larger and stronger then ever,
with clear Jewish majority, united Israeli sovereignty and
worldwide recognition as the capital of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Barak might be referring to the plan he reportedly proposed at
the Camp David talks, in which Israel will transfer some Arab
villages in East Jerusalem and on the outskirts of Jerusalem to the
Palestinians, while Israel will annex some big settlements into the
Jerusalem municipality. The Palestinians rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Clinton and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
another ardent Mideast mediator, had raised some ideas for
resolving the Jerusalem problem, the key for finally ending the
Israeli-Palestinian conflicts.
</P>
<P>
But there are no signs that any proposals had been accepted by
both sides.
</P>
<P>
Barak and Arafat will both traveled to New York next week to
attend the United Nations' Millenium Summit, on the sidelines of
which they will meet separately with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Barak warned Friday that if it became apparent that Israel could
not found partnership in the negotiations with the Palestinians,
the outcome "will not be simple."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians will face "real tragedy" and the Israelis will
face some serious tests, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are scheduled to declare an independent state
on September 13, but it is now widely believed that they will
postpone the date at least to November.
</P>
<P>
Some Israeli officials also claimed that the two sides should
reach an accord by Jewish New Year, or before September 30.
Otherwise, they said, there will never be a deal.
</P>
<P>
In case that the Palestinians unilaterally declare statehood
without an Israeli-Palestinian agreement, some Israeli legislators
had proposed that Israel should annex its occupied lands in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, and block entry of Palestinian workers
and stop trade, which will surely choke the frail Palestinian
economy.
</P>
<P>
On the other sides, Israelis also worried that Palestinian
extremists will resort to terrorist attacks against Israeli targets
in such a scenario.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Friday that he still has faith and hope that the
other side will show more openness and flexibility at the moment of
truth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
