<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governments Committed Safer, Cleaner, Cheaper Automobiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- An agreement between
governments world-wide committing themselves to harmonize and
improve at global level the safety and environmental performance
of automobiles and other road vehicles formally entered into force
on August 25, 2000, the United Nations Economic Commission for
Europe (UN/ECE) announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Among the signatories of the agreement are the most important
vehicle manufacturing countries, including the United States,
Japan, Germany, France, the United Kingdom, Canada and Russia, as
well as the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of South Africa and Spain have also signed the
agreement although not yet ratified it, and many other countries
are undertaking the necessary legal procedures for acceding to the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Concluded in 1998 after three years of intense negotiations,
this new global agreement provides the framework for the
development of globally agreed vehicle regulations which will
establish the safety, environmental, energy efficiency and anti-
theft performance criteria and limits to which newly manufactured
vehicles throughout the world, their equipment and parts, will
have to comply.
</P>
<P>
The global regulations will address such vehicle components as
braking, tires, lighting and light-signaling, safety glazing,
windscreen defrosting and demisting. They will address the
commonly agreed performance criteria and limits to be complied
with by these components and also harmonized test methods.
</P>
<P>
Developed in the framework of a UN/ECE working party, this 1998
agreement is expected to lead to safer and more environmentally
friendly vehicles, with higher energy efficiency and better anti-
theft protection as well as with lower manufacturing costs.
</P>
<P>
The future global regulations will also be developed by the UN/
ECE working party, which since March 2000 has transformed itself
into the World Forum for Harmonization of Vehicle Regulations,
assisted by six Working Parties specialized in the various main
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0043 </DOCNO>
