<HEADLINE> Chirac Urges More Peace Efforts From Israel, Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Friday urged Israel and Palestinians to make more peace efforts,
saying the peace process has entered a crucial stage.
</P>
<P>
"We have the feeling that we are near the goal, that we need
still a small effort by both sides in order to arrive at this
peace," said Chirac after a meeting with visiting Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
He said that the European Union will join efforts with the
United States to push the peace process, adding that September is
decisive for arriving at peace between Israel and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Chirac also had a telephone conversation with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, discussing particularly the
problem of the status of Jerusalem, the most thorny issue in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, said spokeswoman of the Elysee
presidential palace, Catherine Colonna.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said that the peace talks are at a crucial
moment and everything should be done to remove the last obstacles.
</P>
<P>
"France appeals to the two sides to seize the historic chance,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
The French president is due to meet with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, Barak and other leaders of the Mideast region next
week during the U.N. Millennium Summit in New York.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who arrived here Friday to brief Chirac on the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process, said in an
interview with the weekly magazine Le Figaro that the sovereignty
of Jerusalem is the last obstacle to a peace agreement between
Israel and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He said that Arafat will not give up sovereignty of East
Jerusalem because all Muslims will not forgive him if he does.
</P>
</TEXT>
