<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Economy in Better Shape: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Turkey-desk Chief Carlo Cottarelli said that Turkish
economy "is in obvious recovery" this year after last year's grave
contraction, Turkish Daily News reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cottarelli, who arrived in Istanbul on Thursday for the third
regular review of a three-year stand-by deal, said that the rise in
domestic demand of Turkey "is positive", but its consumption
component should be kept under close scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is implementing the three-year economic stability
program under the four-billion-dollar stand-by deal signed with
the IMF last December.
</P>
<P>
Under the three-year loan package approved by the IMF, Turkey
pledged to reduce its chronic inflation and budget deficits,
undertake a comprehensive privatization program and reform
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The government aims to reduce inflation to 20 percent in 2000,
10 percent in 2001 and 5.0 percent in 2002. The annual inflation
rate stood at 68.9 percent in January of this year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's gross national product (GNP) posted a robust 4.4
percent growth in the second quarter of this year, against a 3.2
percent contraction in the same period of last year, according to
the figures published by the State Statistics Bureau on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts agreed that the government would be able to achieve its
GNP and gross domestic product (GDP) growth targets of 5.5 percent
and 6 percent respectively this year.
</P>
<P>
Cottarelli said that the IMF team will inspect possible measures
on monetary and fiscal policies for next year within the framework
of the 2001 budget plans.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the second review, important developments had
occurred in Turkish fiscal position, particularly structural
changes in the economy.
</P>
<P>
While non-interest surplus increased, he said, interest rates
fell and the inflation rate is on a downward trend.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that "the current account deficit should be kept
under close observation. The rise in oil prices and the boom in
demand at home raised imports, and this left its mark on current
accounts. Rising oil prices not only aggravated current accounts
but inflation as well."
</P>
<P>
Cottarelli said that sustainability of current accounts deficit
is of importance to Turkey, although tourism revenues also went up.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimistic about the privatization program in the
country, saying that it is possible that further progress will be
achieved in Turk Telekom sell-off and other privatizations.
</P>
<P>
After completion of the IMF team's talks, the government will
send a second supplementary letter of intent to Washington,
whereupon the IMF board should release the fourth tranche of the 4
billion dollars stand-by loan, around 300 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The chief of Turkish Treasury Selcuk Demiralp said that "our
eight-month performance is strong, in particular regarding the
budget. We expect positive and significant developments for the
remaining four months. The IMF also has similar expectations."
</P>
<P>
The macro-economic performance so far showed that the government
has sticked to the program, despite unexpected external factors
such as higher world oil prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
He assured that there will be no large deviation from the
program targets. "The more we approach the program targets, the
more we will publicize the success of the program. There is no need
for an extra measure beyond the program we are implementing," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF delegation separated into groups on Thursday and will
start technical studies at the Finance Ministry, State Planning
Organization (DPT), the Treasury and Central Bank of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cottarelli said that the third visit of the IMF is important to
see the whole picture in 2000 and to determine the macro-economic
targets of 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
