<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Calls for Robust Parliaments in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
United Nations Kofi Annan on Friday emphasized role of the
parliamentary process in ensuring good governance in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Robust parliaments pave the way to peaceful coexistence and
harmony in our societies," Annan said in the message delivered by
Lalla Ben Barka, deputy executive secretary of the UN Economic
Commission for Africa, at the opening ceremony of the Fourth
Africa Governance Forum in the Ugandan capital Kampala.
</P>
<P>
"Better governance means, among other things, the greater
participation of all citizens in the decisions that affect their
lives," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"There is also a need for more participatory, accountable and
transparent processes of decision-making," he added.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day forum organized by the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) and the Office of Prime Minister of
Uganda, representatives from 16 sub-Saharan African countries will
discuss the contribution of the parliamentary process in
strengthening governance in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"UNDP and the Economic Commission for Africa have made
governance a priority issue in the battle for economic recovery
and human development on the continent," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni said that good governance can
be achieved through harmony between the branches of government -
the executive, the legislature and the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
"We should, therefore, avoid conflict between the branches of
government in the knowledge that we all work for the common good
of the population," said Museveni in his address read by Prime
Minister Appolo Nsibambi.
</P>
<P>
The conference provides a platform for Africans, international
organizations and Africa's external development partners to engage
in dialogue on the state of governance on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The third one was held last year in Mali and deliberated on
conflict management and governance. Ghana hosted the second one on
"accountability and transparency in Africa" while the first was
held in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, dealing with issues of leadership
building, strengthening parliamentary, judicial and administrative
systems as well as free and responsible press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South African Racism Conference Enters Third Day  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua)-- South Africans must
be frank about their views on racism if they want to overcome the
problem, South African Human Rights Commissioner Barney Pityana
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Opening the third day of the national conference on racism in
Sandton, Johannesburg, Pityana said: "This is the right place for
South Africans to frankly express their views."
</P>
<P>
"People need to express their feelings as we cannot go forward
if they do not overcome their anger," he said.
</P>
<P>
 Pityana earlier warned political parties not to dominate the
discussions and politicize the conference.
</P>
<P>
"This is the platform for all those views should be aired ---
but it can only take place where there is tolerance and mutual
respect between the participants," he said.
</P>
<P>
Friday is seen as the most important day of the four-day
conference. Discussions will centre around strategies to combat
racism.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which costs 4 million rand (about 2.8 million
U.S. dollar) to mount, has attracted more than 1500 delegates.
</P>
</TEXT>
