<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United States to Play Hosts to Guatemala in World Cup Qualifier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After a 1-1 away tie on July 16, the United States will play
the hosts on Sunday in Washington against Guatemala, with its fans
reportedly to disrupt Guatemala's preparations through their "
project mayhem" to keep the visitors from sleeping Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
While not endorsing the disruptive pranks, the U.S. soccer
federation is not discouraging it either.
</P>
<P>
"This is America. We appreciate that fans have the right to
express their support in many ways," said USSF spokesman Jim
Moorhouse.
</P>
<P>
U.S. coach Bruce Arena doesn't mind, saying "things like this
are done everywhere we go, it's interesting to see if our people
can be at all effective."
</P>
<P>
In the earlier match in July, Guatemala employed gamesmanship
by moving the venue from comfortable Guatemala city to muggy
Mazatenango. Its fans blared music all night to keep the Americans
awake.
</P>
<P>
Now it's paytime time. The American fans are planning to set
off car alarms to disrupt sleep, to order pizzas to be delivered
in the middle of the night and to delay service of the Guatemalans
' chartered bus.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Costa Rica leads the four-team group with two wins
against one loss, followed by the American and Guatemala, both
tied in 1-1-1, and Barbodos tailed with one win against two losses.
</P>
<P>
The Americans still have Costa Rica on October 11 in Columbus,
Ohio, and are away at Barbados on November 15. The top two teams
will advance to the final qualifying round next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
