<HEADLINE> Agassi not to Blame Loss on Family Grief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On Thursday, Agassi became the fourth top seed to lost in the
first two rounds since the Open era began in 1968, when he was
defeated by Clement in the second round 6-3, 6-2 and 6-4 in one
hour and 42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know what to tell you, you've got to give people
credit where credit's due," said Agassi, "Clement made an
adjustment, started playing bigger and I never raised my level."
</P>
<P>
Those close to Agassi said he needs time to sort through his
feelings after he disclosed on Tuesday that his mother and sister
were suffering breast cancers.
</P>
<P>
But Agassi repeatedly rejected suggestions that it might be the
reason he has won only one title at the Australian Open this year.
He pointed instead to the physical woes he's experienced since
playing Davis Cup for the United States against Zimbabwe in Harare.
</P>
<P>
On the feasibility of refraining from competing in the Olympic
Games due to the loss and illness of his loved ones, Agassi said:
"I've learned enough to know not to jump to too many conclusions
too quickly, we'll have to wait and see." 
</P>
</TEXT>
