<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL to Assess Party Position at Grassroots Level for Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina, who last week said her party Awami League (AL) will
go alone in the next general elections, sent party's student
members to the 64 districts of the country Friday to assess the
party position at the grassroots level beforehand.
</P>
<P>
In the backdrop of the opposition's decision to form electoral
alliance in the next general elections, Prime Minister and AL
chief Hasina assigned some 100 former and present leaders of the
party's student wing for fact-finding Wednesday night and sent
them to all the 64 districts Friday to prepare secret reports on
the party position at the grassroots level, party sources said.
</P>
<P>
Each team will have to visit at least three districts before
returning to the capital by September 6.
</P>
<P>
"We are asked to assess organizational strength and weakness of
the party at the district level, party position before the next
year's parliament elections and intra-party feuds in every
districts," disclosed a former student leader preferring anonymity.
</P>
<P>
When asked about reports of intra-party bickering and resultant
incidents of violence in the recent weeks, the party sources said
that Hasina was well aware of the developments and would issue
appropriate directives to AL leadership at the upper level.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister asked the student leaders to have their
reports ready before September 11, the day she returns from New
York after attending the United Nations Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the prime minister had, however, given no
indication as to whether any action would be taken on the basis of
the survey reports.
</P>
<P>
"Our duty is to report to the party chief about the
troublemakers within the party. She did not give us any idea
whether any actions will follow or not," said one source.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here termed Hasina's move as "pragmatic,"
saying that based on the reports, the Awami League should be able
to fix correct strategy for winning the next national elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
