<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Leave Decision on NMD to Successor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has decided to leave a decision on whether to deploy a national
missile defense (NMD) shield to his successor, agencies reports
quoted officials as saying on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a speech slated for 11 a.m. EDT (1500 GMT) Friday at
Georgetown University, Clinton will announce that he has decided
against taking steps to begin building an anti-missile radar in
Alaska, which would be the first step in deploying a national
missile shield.
</P>
<P>
The proposed NMD, projected to cost about 60 billion U.S.
dollars, is designed to protect all 50 U.S. states against attack
by a limited number of long-range ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said Clinton made his decision after thoroughly
reviewing recommendations from his senior advisers and based his
move on the four criteria laid out for decision: threat, cost,
technical feasibility and its overall impact on national security.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said earlier Friday that
Clinton will talk about national security and his decision on
national missile defense in a speech at Georgetown University. But
he did not specify what decision Clinton will announce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
