<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Games Could Be Hit by Flu Outbreak: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Sydney Olympics is a
prime target for an influenza outbreak, a World Health
Organization (WHO) flu expert warned Friday in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
Alan Hampson, of the WHO's Collaborating Center For Influenza,
said the Olympics were being staged around the peak of the flu
season, with three flu strains now circulating in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Hampson said in an interview that crowding provided the ideal
environment for the spread of the flu.
</P>
<P>
And highly-trained athletes at the peak of their preparation
had a lower resistance.
</P>
<P>
"If I was an Olympic athlete, I would have had my flu shots,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Hampson said Australia's influenza season peaked between July
and September, but it was uncertain what would happen in Sydney in
the leadup to the Games.
</P>
<P>
"It may vanish and it may increase," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
