<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, Bhutan Extend Trade Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and Bhutan Friday
extended their existing trade pact for three years to boost trade
between the two neighbors for mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed an agreed minutes following two-day
official talks between visiting Bhutanese Foreign secretary Dasho
Ugyen Tshering and Bangladesh Commerce Secretary Golam Rahman.
</P>
<P>
The Dhaka and Thimpu trade agreement which is due to expire
next week, was signed in 1980. It was renewed in 1990 for another
10 years.
</P>
<P>
The Bhutanese foreign secretary arrived here on August 29 at
the head of an eight-member delegation.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two countries agreed that the list of
Bhutanese export items would be enlarged and Bangladesh would also
try to add more items in its export basket to the landlocked
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also agreed to hold trade talks in Thimpu in 2001 to
boost bilateral trade. The annual trade between the two countries
is around 10 million U.S. dollars with the balance of trade tilted
to Bhutan.
</P>
<P>
Briefing newsmen here Friday after talks with the Bhutanese
foreign secretary, Golam Rahman said that the Bhutan delegation
proposed free trade with Bangladesh like it has with India. "
Bangladesh will consider Bhutan's proposal," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
