<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RABAT -- Moroccan trade balance deficit reached 22.6 billion
dirhams (about 2.2 billion U.S. dollars) in the first six months of
this year, a surge of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Arabic daily Al-Haiyat quoted an official release as saying that
the rising oil bill that hit 780 million dollars by June 3, up by
151 percent from the same period of last year affected Morocco's
imports. And the Morocco will pay 1.6 billion dollars for importing
oil by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish hazelnut export season for 2000-2001
starts on September 1 and a total of 225,000 tons are expected to
export this year, reported Turkish Daily News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Turkey exported 200,000 tons for 700 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turkey produces most of the hazelnuts consumed in the world on
54,000 hectares of land.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Administrative Court in Bursa, northwest Turkey,
cancelled the construction permission for the U.S.-owned Cargill
Agriculture Industry and Trade Corporation near Iznik Lake in the
province, reported Turkish Daily News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The court ruling came after nongovernmental organizations'
complaints that the starch plant was being constructed on 194 acres
of prime farmland.
</P>
<P>
The court ruled that the Supreme Planning Board's granting of
permission for the construction of a plant on land described in the
regional charts as having soil whose arable quality should be
protected, amounted to a serious planning defect and a usurpation
of authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
