<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Rules Out Imminent Iraqi Missiles Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said Friday that he did not know any evidence of imminent
missiles attacks from Iraq, but Israel is always ready for the
possibility.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that a U.S. Army Patriot anti-missile
battery in Germany was on alert for possible raid against Israel,
because Iraq, as the U.S. officials said, wanted to launch attacks
against the Jewish state during the political vacuum in Washington
in the next few weeks for presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
However, Barak, quoted by Israel Radio, said during a tour to
schools in central Israel, "I am not sure any more that we must
truly be worried and I don't know whether this Patriot battery must
truly be worried."
</P>
<P>
But Israel do get ready for the threats from Iraq, the prime
minister added. "I can promise that we are ready and are following
well all that is happening," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel regards Iraq as a major threat in the region. During the
1991 Gulf War triggered by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait a year
earlier, Iraq launched Scud missiles on Israeli targets but caused
no casualties.
</P>
<P>
In December 1998, when the gulf tensions escalated once more due
to Iraq's refusal to cooperate with what it called "unfair" U.N.
weapon inspection, the U.S. deployed Patriots battery again to
Israel. But Iraq fired no missiles at Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
