<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Exports Reach All-Time High in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The value of Indonesia's
exports reached the all-time high in July this year with a record
of 5.353 billion U.S. dollars or 1.17 percent higher than the
figure in June when it stood at 5.291 billion U.S. dollars, the
National Bureau of Statistic (NBS) announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
During January-July this year, the country's exports reached 34.
653 billion U.S. dollars, 33.68 percent higher over the same
period last year, NBS' Chairwomen Sudarti Surbakti said at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
She said that non-oil/gas exports reached 4.204 billion dollars
in July this year or increased by 1.16 percent from the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
"Cumulatively, the exports value for non-oil/gas commodities in
seven months has increased by 26.90 percent to 27.027 billion U.S.
dollars," she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the exports value for oil and gas commodities also
increased by 1.18 percent to 1.149 billion U.S. dollars in July
this year.
</P>
<P>
Surbakti also disclosed that the country's imports value was
also up slightly in July by 2.34 percent to 2.485 billion U.S.
dollars against the previous month figure when it only reached 2.
429 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"During January-July 2000, the value of imports reached 16.192
billion U.S. dollars or 19.58 percent higher over the same period
last year," she said.
</P>
<P>
She revealed that import for non-oil/gas in July this year
reached 1.989 billion dollars or increased by 1.69 percent from
the previous month.
</P>
<P>
"While cumulatively, the non-oil/gas import value reached 13.
046 billion U.S. dollars or rose by 10.20 percent," she said.
</P>
<P>
This year's imports of non-oil/gas commodities were dominated
by machines and mechanical equipment. "The value of import for
machines and mechanical equipment during January-July reached 2.
022 billion U.S. dollars or 15.51 percent of the total imports,"
Surbakti added.
</P>
<P>
She further added that imports for consumption goods in the
first six months was recorded at 1.154 billion U.S. dollars or up
by 6.40 percent against the same period last year, while imports
for raw materials and capital goods rose by 18.77 percent and 27.
90 percent respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
