<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Govt Rejects Rebels' Demands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Sierra Leonean government
has rejected the fresh demands of the rebel group known as the
West Side Boys who are still holding seven soldiers in the war-
torn west African country, said a report reaching here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean Information Minister Julius Spencer was quoted
as saying in the capital Freetown that the rebels had made no
demands directly to the government and therefore their demands
made public to the media would not be met.
</P>
<P>
Spencer stressed that the government would not be subjected to
such pressure. He warned the West Side Boys they risked criminal
charges if they continued with their actions.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Cambodia, spokesman for the rebel group, demanded on
Thursday that they wanted a review of the Lome Peace Accord, their
reintegration into the government army as well as the release of
their supporters from jail.
</P>
<P>
A total of 12 soldier, 11 Britons and one Sierra Leonean, were
captured by the West Side Boys last Friday when they were
patrolling along the Freetown-Masiaka highway. Five British
soldiers were released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia disclosed that the remaining hostages were well
treated and being properly fed and provided with adequate medicine
and shelter, but he said they would not release the captives
unless their new demands were met.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for the release of the remaining soldiers were
reportedly under way between the Sierra Leonean government, the
United Nations Mission in Sierra Leone, the British and the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Cuts Number of Angolan Aid Receivers to 1.1 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
has announced that it can only assure assistance to some 1.1
million war-displaced Angolans until November instead of the
originally planned 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
Speaking here on Thursday, WFP spokeswoman Maria Flynn said her
organization made the decision mainly due to the diminishing food
stocks and the slow-pace donation. Only 51 percent of the aid
promised by donor countries for the year 2000 had been delivered
by the end of August, as against 42 percent by late May, she said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that in late June, the Rome-based U.N. aid
agency warned that the relief food would run out at the end of
August unless there were "immediate emergency donations".
</P>
<P>
In September, there exists a call for distributing 16,000 tons
of food products to various Angolan provinces, especially those
located in the central highland, where the residents have seen the
most fierce civil conflicts.
</P>
<P>
After 26 years of civil war, there are some 3.7 million
displaced persons around the southwest African country, most of
them being short of food, potable water, medicaments and other
living necessities.
</P>
<P>
WFP assistant director for Africa Tesema Negash and its global
logistics and transports chief David Kaatrud are currently in
Angola for a 10-day visit, with an aim to evaluate the current
humanitarian situation and prepare aid operations for the year
2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some 30,000 Displaced People Resettled in Central Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- At least 30,000 war-displaced
people camped in Angola's central province of Kwanza-sul are being
resettled in productive areas, the official news agency Angop
reported here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The resettlement is being carried out jointly by the local
municipal authorities of Seles, located in southern Kwanza-sul,
and the charity organization German Agro Action (AAD), the news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Seles municipal authorities has decided to supply the
displaced persons with some 5,000 hectares of field for
cultivation, while the German non-governmental organization
provides working tools, domestic utensils, construction materials,
assorted foodstuffs, clothes and other goods.
</P>
<P>
According to Mayor Joao Baptista of Seles, the resettlement of
the displaced persons in fertile areas with relative security is
aimed to change the fact that the displaced persons rely too much
on charity and donations which have never been sufficient for
their needs.
</P>
<P>
With the development of the military situation around the
country in favor of the government troops, the Angolan government
has begun resettling the large number of war-displaced persons,
with the self-sufficient program as the main means, especially for
those living in the central highland.
</P>
<P>
AAD project director Armando de Almeida said they are planning
to construct two schools, with four rooms each, and a medical post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Urges Guinea to Curb Liberian Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Taylor has urged his Guinean counterpart Lansana Conte to tackle
Liberian rebels allegedly based in Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Liberian government forces have been fighting rebels in the
north of the country since the rebels allegedly invaded the
country from Guinea about two month ago. Most of the fighting has
taken place in Lofa County bordering Guinea.
</P>
<P>
"I do not have a problem with Lansana Conte personally. We can
engage Guinea in dialogue to put a halt to the bust-up. This
government does not have a problem with Guinea," Taylor said on
state radio Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need for the Guinean government to take the war in
Lofa seriously so that its territory should not be used," he said.
</P>
<P>
He has accused Guinea of harboring Liberian dissidents bent on
toppling his government, a charge Guinea repeatedly rejects.
</P>
</TEXT>
