<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Athletic Association Elects New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Amateur Athletic
Association held congress here Friday electing Suresh Kalmadi,
president of the Amateur Athletic Federation of India, as its new
president for period 2000-2004.
</P>
<P>
The congress also elected new vice presidents. Sheikh Khalid
bin Thani al-Thani of Qatar retained his post as senior vice
president and Shang Xiutang of China and other four officials were
elected as new vice president.
</P>
<P>
Kalmadi told reporters that he will take measures to popularize
athletics in the region and introduce more competitions in Asia on
the pattern of the International Amateur Athletic Federation (IAAF)
Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
"Currently our athletes hardly get a high level of competition
with the result that they have to go all the way to compete in
Europe and the U.S., which is financially unaffordable for both --
the federations and the athletes," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new president said he plan to tie up with television
companies to broadcast the Asian Athletics Programme throughout
the region and other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
"This will bring in much needed revenue by selling rights and
also act to popularize the sport. But this will only be possible
by increasing the number of competition," he added.
</P>
<P>
Explaining other plans, Kalmadi said he will set up one
coaching center per region which will be sponsored by the AAAA. He
will also initiate special steps for junior programme, development
of coaches and introducing more scientific and medical support to
Asian athletes, and provide financial and technical assistance to
the developing countries in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Kalmadi, former railway minister, now holds the post of
President of the Indian Olympic Association, President of the
South Asia Amateur Athletic Federation and Chairman of the Afro-
Asian Games Organizing Committee. The first Afro-Asian Games is
scheduled to be held in New Delhi, India, in November 2001.
</P>
<P>
"These (Afro-Asian) Games will be a big boost for Afro-Asian
solidarity," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The congress Friday also decided to hold the next Asian Track
and Field Championships in Sri Lanka in 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
