<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Standard Chartered to Buy Part of Chase's Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Standard Chartered PLC
announced Friday that it has signed an agreement with The Chase
Manhattan Bank to acquire its consumer banking and credit card
business in Hong Kong for around 1.32 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This means Standard Chartered will replace the Hongkong
Shanghai Banking Corporation to become the biggest credit card
operator in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Chase's consumer banking business in Hong Kong currently has
around 740,000 cards issued. Following the acquisition, Standard
Chartered will have more than 1.9 million cards in issue and a 25
percent market share.
</P>
<P>
The purchase of the Chase Hong Kong consumer banking operation,
which has deposits of approximately two billion U.S. dollars, will
add four branches, four FlexiBanking Centers and 40 ATMs, to
Standard Chartered's existing 80 branches and 186 Moneylink ATMs.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition will be funded from cash raised by the sale of
Chartered Trust and by way of a placing of new ordinary shares.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered said that it has sold Chartered Trust, the
group's UK and Channel Islands consumer finance and contract hire
businesses, to Lloyds UDT, a subsidiary of Lloyds TSB Group,
Britain's biggest retail bank, for 627 million British pounds (915
million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
