<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Revised Patent Law Compatible to International Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China's top intellectual
property official pointed out Friday that the newly-revised patent
law is a milestone in the country's intellectual property process
and compatible to concerned international covenants.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference organized by the State Council
Information Office, Jiang Ying, commissioner of the State
Intellectual Property Office (SIPO), said the second revision to
the patent law will introduce a far-reaching influence on China's
scientific and technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee,
China's top legislature, adopted on August 25 the second
amendments to the patent law, which will be effective from July 1,
2001.
</P>
<P>
According to the revised law, the State-owned enterprises will
enjoy the same treatment as other enterprises as far as the rights
and obligations relating to filing and obtaining patents.
</P>
<P>
The law also includes articles that define the service inventor
should be remunerated and awarded, strengthen patent protections,
improve judicial and administrative enforcement, streamline
procedure of patent examinations and grants, and introduce an
impartial and efficient patent examinations system and
administration.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, China has adopted the patent law, which was first
revised in 1992. Up till the end of February 2000, China has
received one million patent applications and set up an effective
mechanism for patent protection.
</P>
<P>
The practice over the last decade proves that patent
legislation has played a great role in safeguarding and promoting
the development of China's Intellectual Property, Jiang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Implements Revised Air Pollution Prevention Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China started to implement the
revised Air Pollution Prevention Law today.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, discharging pollutants more than the
state standards violates the law.
</P>
<P>
The law provides important regulations concerning the control
of coal burning, the ban of highly-polluting fuel in heavily-
polluted cities, and promotes the use of clean energy, said Xie
Zhenhua, director of the State Environment Protection
Administration (SEPA).
</P>
<P>
He said regulations on the inspection of manufacturing,
repairing and fuel-burning of vehicles, quota management of the
production and import of products which can cause depletion of
ozone layer have also been added to the law.
</P>
<P>
The SEPA will cooperate with local governments to work out a
list of key cities for air pollution prevention and will submit
the list to the State Council for approval.
</P>
<P>
The administration will take the pollution of suspended
particles as one of index for the inspection of environmental
pollution in cities, and will issue the program for the areas of
acid rain and sulfur dioxide control.
</P>
<P>
China's Air Pollution Prevention Law was issued in September of
1987, and was revised for the first time in August of 1995. The
revision of the law this year is aimed to take more effective
measures to control air pollution nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Inspect Safety Facilities in Scenic Areas Before National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China has begun a nationwide
inspection on safety facilities in scenic areas, in an effort to
ensure the safety of tourists during the forthcoming National Day
holiday, which falls on October 1st.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from China's tourism department shows that during
the seven days of the Labor Day holiday in May, some 46 million
Chinese traveled, posing a grave threat to safety facilities,
especially in scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
In order to make preparations for the National Day holiday, the
Ministry of Public Security issued an urgent notice today, calling
on the departments concerned to organize a thorough safety
inspection on the country's scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
According to the notice, the inspection will focus on the
inspection of amusement facilities, restaurants and hotels, as
well as traffic facilities, so as to prevent potential outbreaks
of fire, explosions and traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
The notice also calls on travel service agencies and
administrative bureaus concerned to establish and implement safety
measures.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry is scheduled to dispatch special teams to conduct
random inspections in certain areas, the notice says.
</P>
<P>
A total of 21 cities, including Beijing, Chengde, and Dunhuang,
as well as 10 scenic spots such as Huangshan Mountain and the
Wutaishan Mountain, are top on the agenda of the forthcoming
nationwide inspection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
