<HEADLINE> Thai Bourse Ends Higher After Banks' Rating Upgrades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 1 (Xinhua)-- Thai stocks end higher Friday
amid active volume on buying in banking stocks, following three
banks' rating upgrades.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index closed up 2.9 points,
at 310.73, from 307.83 Thursday. The blue-chip SET 50 index is up
0.23 point at 21.84.
</P>
<P>
Volume is quite active at 255.2 million shares worth 2.42
billion baht (59 million U.S. dollars) as Friday is the first day
of brokerage fees' floor reduction for retail investors to 0.25
percent from 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Advancers have outnumbered decliners 110 to 46, with 95
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Fitch IBCA, an international rating agency, announced late
Thursday it had upgraded the individual ratings of Siam Commercial
Bank, Thai Military Bank and DBS Thai Danu Bank, while affirming
the ratings of four other banks.
</P>
<P>
Investors are reacting in response to the rating revision,
pushing the banking sector 5.93 points, or 3.83 percent higher.
Thai Military Bank is up 3.51 percent, while DBS Thai Danu is up 1.
2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The finance sector is 1.27 percent higher on local speculative
buying after the Thai bourse officially announced the start of
brokerage fee liberalization will be on October 1. National
Finance is 1.82 percent higher and KGI Securities One has gained 4.
35 percent. 
</P>
