<HEADLINE> Prospective Suspects in Human Rights Violation in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Chief of the
Investigation Team Into Human Rights Serious Offense in East Timor,
M.A. Rahman announced here Friday that as many as 19 prospective
suspects were allegedly responsible in the human rights violation
in the Indonesian breakaway province of East Timor last year.
</P>
<P>
Rahman said in a press conference at the attorney general
office, that the names of the prospective suspects are the field
functionaries when the abuse was taking place.
</P>
<P>
However, former Chief of the Indonesian Military (TNI) General
Wiranto was not included in the list of the names.
</P>
<P>
Based on the team's report, the highest ranking officer of the
TNI who was recommended to be declared as suspect was Maj. General
Adam Damiri, a former Commander of the Udayana Military Command
overseeing the former province.
</P>
<P>
While from the civilian, former Governor of East Timor, Abilio
Jose Osario Soares was listed.
</P>
<P>
Rahman added that further investigation will start on September
5 this year.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people were killed and tens of thousands fled their
homes in East Timor last September when pro-Jakarta militiamen
went on a frenzy of destruction after the people voted on August
30 for independence in a UN-sponsored ballot. 
</P>
