<HEADLINE> Shanghai B-Share Market Weekly Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai B-share market
sped up its recent slide this week, plagued by listless sentiment
after the market's attempt to advance had fizzled out.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai B-share index nosed-dived 8.26 points or 11.36
percent to a one-month low of 64.48 points at the end of the week,
posting its largest weekly decline in more than one year.
</P>
<P>
The five-day turnover contracted to 1.26 billion yuan (152.19
million US dollars), which was 60.36 percent less than the total
of last week.
</P>
<P>
The sudden meltdown, started on August 22, continued to weigh
on the market. Taking no additional positive signs from the latest
earnings season, coming to an end this Thursday, investors were
less confident of the direction, according to Homeway, China's
leading on-line financial and securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
For the past couple of days, the market had been deteriorating.
As investors had been in a selling mood, the market incurred a
broad slump, with market breadth decidedly negative. It failed to
materialize a recovery, leaving the index stuck around its lows.
</P>
<P>
The only relief from the past week may be the fact that selling
had been easing with trading volume on the lighter side.
</P>
<P>
Homeway analysts say that it will still be the bear's day in
the week ahead as the market is mostly likely to trade with choppy
and fragile sentiment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
