<HEADLINE> Shenzhen B-Share Market Weekly Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Shenzhen B-share incurred
impressive losses this week, unable to reverse courses from its
latest slump for lack of momentum amid investors' conviction that
the market has to wait for some time to revive.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen B-share index plunged 8.21 points or 6.49 percent
to a one-month low of 118.28 at the end of the week, posting its
largest weekly decline in more than one year.
</P>
<P>
The weekly turnover contracted to 699.91 million HK dollars,
which was 58.36 percent less than the total of last week,
according to Homeway, China's leading on-line financial and
securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
The sudden meltdown, started on August 22, continued to weigh
on the market. Taking no additional positive signs from the latest
earnings season, coming to an end this Thursday, investors were
less confident of the direction.
</P>
<P>
For the past couple of days, the market had been deteriorating.
As investors were inclined to a selling trend, the market was
plagued by a broad drag, with almost all areas moving lingering in
the red. It failed to materialize a recovery, leaving the index
stuck around its lows.
</P>
<P>
The only relief from the past week may be the fact that selling
had been easing with trading volume on the lighter side.
</P>
<P>
Homeway analysts predict that it will still be the bear's day
in the week ahead as the market is mostly likely to trade with
choppy and fragile sentiment. 
</P>
