<HEADLINE> China's T-bond Weekly Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese treasuries were weak
though the domestic stock market plunged late this week.
</P>
<P>
Four of the six current treasuries lost, led by 009704 and the
new floating-rate 010004. One bond saw a tame rise of 0.09 yuan
and the remaining one unchanged, according to Homeway, China's
leading on-line financial and securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
Bond 009704 plummeted by 0.87 yuan to 145.28 yuan compared with
the close price on last Friday, buoying the yield up 0.12
percentage points to 3.88 percent. Having kept dropping through
this week, the room for a further slip is limited. The bond is
expected to recoup some of the losses in the following trading
days.
</P>
<P>
The ten-year floating-rate 010004, whose coupon rate is 2.87
percent this year, tumbled by 0.31 yuan to 104.50 yuan,
accompanied by a 0.03 percentage-point gain in the yield, which
closed at 2.40 percent.
</P>
<P>
New listing rules on the corporate bond on the Shanghai and
Shenzhen stock markets, released on Thursday, will take effect
from September 1 this year. The new rules give details not only on
the application procedure, document preparation, and
responsibilities of listing sponsors, but also on the timely
information disclosure and trade suspension, resumption and
delisting.
</P>
<P>
The move aims to bring the regulations more in line with the
current Securities Law, Company Law and Regulations on Corporate
Bond Management, according to the China Securities Regulatory
Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
