<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Sees 4.4 Percent of GNP Growth in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's gross national product
(GNP) posted a robust 4.4 percent growth in the second quarter of
this year, against a 3.2 percent contraction in the same period of
last year, Turkish Daily News reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Based on the provisional figures published by the State
Statistics Bureau on Thursday, analysts agreed that the government
would be able to achieve its GNP and gross domestic product (GDP)
growth targets of 5.5 percent and 6 percent respectively this year.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth in the second quarter was 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts had predicted a modest growth for the second quarter
due to effects of the base period, which was the strongest last
year.
</P>
<P>
The figures carried Turkey's first half GNP growth to 4.3
percent and GDP growth to 5.7 percent, combined with 4.2 percent
and 5.6 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter, foreign trade posted a strong 10.6
percent growth with a 26.3 percent rise of import taxes while
industry grew by a modest 4 percent, still edging up from the first
quarter's 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the agriculture sector was 2.3 percent in the second
quarter, sending the figure of the first six months of this year to
1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Import-related activities such as trade, transport and
communications enjoyed a significant growth in the first half of
this year on the back of soaring imports," said Altug Karamenderes,
senior economist of Istanbul-based brokerage house Ata Yatirim.
</P>
<P>
He said that "compared to 1998, which was not an economic
recession year, the impact of trade, transport and communications
on growth is positive, but that of industry and agriculture is
negative."
</P>
<P>
"Assuming 1998 as a base year of 100, GNP is 100.8 in the first
half of this year. That 0.8 percentage point growth above 1998
meant an approximately 5 billion U.S. dollar current account
deficit to Turkey," the economist added.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit of the first five months this year
was seen at 4.5 billion dollars, compared with a 431 million
dollars surplus last year when the economy shrank by a record 6.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The construction sector contracted by 0.4 percent in the first
half of this year, largely because of a regulatory suspension of
activity.
</P>
<P>
Another senior economist Baturalp Candemir said that the figures
were suggesting that the government will achieve its growth target
this year.
</P>
<P>
"We are expecting GNP and GDP growths of around 6-6.5 percent in
the second half of this year, mainly because of weak base year
effects," the economist said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's GNP contracted by 7.4 percent and 6.1 percent in the
third and fourth quarters of 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Although there is a continued strong demand for durable
consumer goods and services, there is also an increase in
investment spending," Candemir said.
</P>
<P>
"Both the private sector's machinery and equipment investments
and public sector's non-building construction have increased
substantially, which is a good sign," he added.
</P>
<P>
Karamenderes predicted that the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) will urge Turkey to take measures such as tax and interest
rate increase in order not to compromise the inflation target.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is implementing a three-year economic stability programme
under a four-billion-dollar stand-by deal signed with the IMF last
December.
</P>
<P>
Under the three-year loan package approved by the IMF, Turkey
pledged to reduce its chronic inflation and budget deficits,
undertake a comprehensive privatization program and reform
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The government aims to reduce inflation to 20 percent in 2000,
10 percent in 2001 and 5.0 percent in 2002. The annual inflation
rate stood at 68.9 percent in January of this year.
</P>
<P>
Candemir also foresaw that the government would introduce fiscal
measures some time in the second half of this year in a bid both to
contain the current account deficit and to contribute to next
year's primary fiscal surplus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
