<HEADLINE> Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary, September 1  Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary, Friday, September 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING -- In 2000, a series of positive changes has occurred
in China's economy, overcoming the difficulties brought about by
the financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Peiyan, minister of the State Development Planning
Commission, made the remarks at a meeting discussing the economic
situation in China.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the minister said the declining of the economic
growth in the country has been brought to a stop and the efforts
to assist money-losing state-owned enterprises have made important
gains, the official said, noting that the current economic
situation has laid a good foundation for the accomplishment of the
year's economic goal and future development.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC)
Thursday signed agreements with eight Internet service providers
to jointly launch Business-to-Commerce on-line shopping with Peony
credit card.
</P>
<P>
The new business, to be first launched in Beijing and Zhejiang,
will enable Peony credit card holders to do on-line shopping.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ICBC, China's largest state-owned
commercial bank, said launching of the new business marks the ICBC
's access into the field of individual on-line banking business,
including corporate financing, individual financing as well as B-
to-B and B-to-C on-line payment.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The Indian government Thursday liberalized foreign
direct investment (FDI) to facilitate 100 percent foreign
investment in certain telecommunication areas as well as special
economic zones (SEZ) in the country, an official spokesman said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters of the government decision after a cabinet
meeting, the spokesman said India would also allow overseas
venture capital funds to invest in domestic ventures subject to
approval by the Security and Exchange Board of India.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
YANTAI -- China will bring in more investment and up-to-date
technology from abroad to mine for and collect its gold resources,
a senior Chinese trade official said today.
</P>
<P>
The country will open more fund-raising channels to help pay
for the mining of gold and adopt a multi-outlet investment system,
said Wang Dexue, director-general of the Gold Administration under
the State Economic and Trade Commission (SETC), at the Fourth
China (International) Gold and Rare Metal Annual Symposium, which
opened today in Zhaoyuan, in east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Some administrative charges in China's western areas
will be reduced and price controls relaxed, the State Development
Planning Commission announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The price initiatives are intended to help create conditions
that will help propel the development of western China, a national
priority.
</P>
<P>
Price controls over such sectors as transportation, education,
environmental protection and construction will be eased, according
to China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Local price administrations have been told to cut
administrative charges deemed excessive and eliminate any
industrial price-fixing that has not been approved by authorities,
China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam registered an export turnover of more than 9.2
billion U.S. dollars in the first eight months of this year, a
year-on-year increase of 27.4 percent, according to Vietnam News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The country's state-owned sector contributed 4.85 billion
dollars, a 7.8-percent year-on-year increase, and the foreign-
invested sector, 4.35 billion dollars, a 59.8-percent increase,
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Boosted by strong global demand, Thai exports
reached 6 billion U.S. dollars in July, the highest monthly level
since 1993, the Bank of Thailand, the central bank, said in a
report here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 22.7-percent expansion in July exports from the same period
of last year was better than the central bank's expectations,
given the decline trend of exports in the second quarter this year,
it noted.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia recorded a trade surplus for the 33rd
consecutive month in July 2000, but the amount was lower than a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
In July 2000, a trade surplus of 4 billion ringgit (1.05
billion U.S. dollars) was achieved against the 5.9 billion ringgit
(1.55 billion dollars) recorded in the same month a year ago,
according to the statistics released here Friday by the Statistics
Department.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- A newly revised law on product quality came into
effect Friday to offer effective legal guarantee for China's
quality promotion.
</P>
<P>
In the coming five to 10 years, economic competition will focus
on quality competition and the improvement of China-made products
will be a key factor in China's economic development, said Li
Chuanqing, director of the State Bureau of Quality and Technical
Supervision.
</P>
<P>
The amended product quality law includes 74 articles, compared
with 51 in the original version.
</P>
<P>
Li said at a meeting marking the implementation of the new law
here Friday that under the revised law, anyone selling fake or
inferior products will be severely punished. 
</P>
