<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Bank Notes Out of Circulation in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Angola's bank notes of the old
currency unit Readjusted Kwanza is out of circulation in the
market as from September 1, according to a document issued by the
Angolan National Bank (BNA) here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Holders of the Readjusted Kwanza notes can still have them
exchanged for notes of the new currency unit Kwanza at BNA's
counters in the provinces of Luanda, Cabinda Huila and Benguela,
within a period of five years from now, the BNA document said.
</P>
<P>
The document quoted BNA director Jorge Leao Peres for issuing
and credit as saying that the central bank has already created
mechanisms to avoid possible constraints to the citizens and
monetary policy tools to check financial imbalances.
</P>
<P>
He said when the Readjusted Kwanza started its circulation in
July of 1995, there was a process of reforms and monetary
adjustment to address the high levels of inflation which required
large quantities of bank notes for transaction.
</P>
<P>
In December 1999, the corrosion of the purchasing power of the
currency prompted the need to introduce a new monetary
readjustment to adapt the circulating bills to the volume of
transactions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"People in the past would talk of billions but in real terms it
represented nothing, and this started creating difficulties to the
accounting process of companies," the BNA official said, noting
that then it became necessary to write off the six zeros from the
old bank notes with a view to suit the currency to the volume of
transactions.
</P>
<P>
As for the new bank notes, which have been circulating for nine
months, Peres said the circulation is positive not only for
facilitating the process of transactions but also for bringing a
good process in bank operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
