<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (recast) 200 Million Chinese Students Begin New Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 200 million Chinese
middle and primary school students went to campus and began their
new terms today.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Ministry of Education (MOE) said revised
teaching materials for senior high school students will be pushed
from this term, and experts have already completed the revision of
teaching materials for compulsory education.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the interests and technology development of students,
new teaching materials and outlines have deleted contents outdated
or exceeded student's capability.
</P>
<P>
Li Lianning, director of elementary education department under
MOE said lacking creative ideas is the main gap between China's
elementary education and that of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Teaching materials of most Chinese schools exceed the actual
capability of the students, according to Yang Deren, dean of
chemistry department of Shanghai Normal University.
</P>
<P>
Under the burden of school work, some students lost interest in
studying, he added.
</P>
<P>
The 2000 Summer Teaching Material Catalog for Primary and
Middle Schools was published by MOE this year, which deleted 39
volumes of teaching material to lessen the study load.
</P>
<P>
Li hopes that more time will be spent in enlarging student's
knowledge, as well as the ability to develop analytical thinking
and reading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
