<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Names New Head of National Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak late Thursday night named outgoing Deputy Chief of General
Staff of Israel Defense Forces (IDF) Uzi Dayan new head of National
Security Council, or Israel's diplomatic planning unit.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that the appointment reinforced Dayan's
chances to be chosen as successor of the current (IDF) Chief of
General Staff Shaul Mofaz, who is scheduled to step down next July,
both Israel's Jerusalem Post and Ha'aretz dailies reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who also holds the Defense portfolio, said Thursday night
that he does view Dayan as "a candidate" for the chief of general
staff. Mofaz has been reportedly at odds with Dayan. But Thursday's
nomination, analysts claimed, has brought a U-turn in the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Dayan, appointed IDF deputy chief of general staff two years
ago, will assume the new post on September 28, according to Barak's
order.
</P>
<P>
The new post, which was vacated by David Levy in January when he
left for Washington as Israeli ambassador there, will give the 52-
year-old popular general a good chance of help the government in
shaping diplomatic and defense strategy.
</P>
<P>
The council deals with various issues such as arms control,
strategy on Iran, which does not recognize Israel, and preparing
Israel's stance on the question of refugees in peace negotiations
with the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
