<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Flies to Paris for Talks on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
flew to Paris on Friday for talks with French leaders on ways of
helping advance the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, accompanied by ministers of foreign affairs and
information, is due to hold talks with French President Jacques
Chirac on Friday and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin on Saturday,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, the key mediator in the Palestinian-Israeli peace
process, is expected to brief French leaders on the consultations
held by parties concerned in an effort to help the Palestinians and
Israel narrow gaps in the final-status negotiations to reach a
balanced agreement.
</P>
<P>
The huge differences between the two sides in the negotiations,
especially over the future of Jerusalem, which both sides want as
their capital, has aborted the Camp David summit, the latest peace
talks brokered by the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Since then, Egypt has received Palestinian, Israeli and U.S.
officials almost daily to assess the situation and discuss a way
out. It is reported that Egypt has also produced new ideas about
the peace process, but the contents of the ideas were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's French tour is the continuation of Egypt's diplomatic
efforts to try to press for a breakthrough on the Palestinian-
Israeli track. France is holding the rotating European Union
presidency.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' leaders will also discuss the Syrian-Israeli
peace talks that foundered in January over disputes between the two
sides on where the border should be. The core issue in the Syrian-
Israeli peace talks is the return of the Golan Heights captured by
Israel from Syria in the 1967 Mideast war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
