<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No U.S. Military Involvement in Hostage Crisis: Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Friday that the United States troops in the Philippines for joint
military exercises will not be allowed to rescue abducted American
Jeffrey Schilling.
</P>
<P>
National Security Adviser Alexander Aguirre made the remarks in
a radio speech as he said that the government would exhaust all
peaceful means to secure Schilling's safe release.
</P>
<P>
"We will always try the peaceful way for the safe release (of
Schilling). Safety of the hostage is primordial in our minds,"
Aguirre said.
</P>
<P>
He also reminded the United States that its elite troops, who
have been in the country since August 14 for military exercises,
must not meddle in the kidnapping case and must respect the
Philippines' sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"They should respect our sovereignty. And they are also bound
by international rules and United Nations principles of non-
interference in the internal affairs of a sovereign state," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said President Joseph
Estrada has accepted the recommendation of Cabinet Cluster E,
which is charged with the handling of the ongoing hostage crisis,
to treat the Schilling incident as a police matter.
</P>
<P>
The United States "recognizes this as an internal affair of the
Philippines," Zamora said, adding that it "will not interfere,
even in just planning a rescue operation."
</P>
<P>
Shilling was abducted by the Abu Sayyaf in Zamboanga City on
Monday and then brought to Jolo island, where five of the original
group of 21 hostages kidnapped from Malaysia in April and two
French journalists are still being held captive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
