<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Requires Financial Institutions to Raise Minimum Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya has
required all financial institutions in the country to raise the
minimum capital level if they hoped to continue operating next
year.
</P>
<P>
"No license for the year 2001 will be issued to any banking
institutions that does not meet the new capital requirements,"
said John Murugu, bank supervision director at the central bank.
</P>
<P>
According to a circular to all financial institutions issued
here Thursday, banks and mortgage finance firms will be required
to raise the minimum capital level to 250 million shillings (about
3.24 million U.S. dollars) by the end of the year from the present
level of 200 million shillings (about 2.6 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Non-banking financial institutions will have a new minimum
capital target of 187.5 million shillings (around 2.43 million
dollars) by December 31 this year, in stead of the present 150
million shillings (around 1.95 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
