<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Alarmed by Spread of Killer Moss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Environment Ministry
has launched an educational drive in a bid to curb the killer moss
(Caulerna taxifolia) from spreading along the country's
Mediterranean coast, reported the Anatolia News Agency on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The moss was reported to be accidentally drained into the
Mediterranean Sea from the Monaco Sea Aquarium and quickly spread
to the Mediterranean coast, causing harm to the French, Italian,
Spanish and Greek coastlines.
</P>
<P>
The Environment Ministry, in cooperation with Dokuz Eylul
University's Sea Science and Technology Institute, has prepared a
program, which is being implemented in Antalya, Kas, Kalkan,
Fethiye and Dalan along the Mediterranean coast.
</P>
<P>
Officials were quoted as saying that the moss is about to invade
Turkey and the program is aimed at waging a widespread campaign to
cope with the dangers of the moss.
</P>
<P>
The problem is that people do not have a reliable and effective
technique to eliminate the moss and the only method that can be
used at this stage is for divers to remove the moss from the water,
according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, we don't know any other way to do away with the
moss. The method we're using is difficult and is not an overall
solution," said the officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
