<HEADLINE> Japan to Evacuate All Residents on Volcanic Miyakejima Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Local authorities on Miyakejima
Island decided Friday to evacuate all residents from the volcanic
island within three days beginning from Saturday due to fears of
massive volcano eruptions, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
Miyakejima village officials are expected to discuss with the
Tokyo metropolitan government an evacuation plan for the some 900
residents still remaining on the island, about 200 km south of
Tokyo, the report said.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the island's 3,800 residents have
already voluntarily left the island for fear of possible
pyroclastic flows, hot mixtures of mud and volcanic material, and
further earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
Smoke from the island's Mt. Oyama volcano rose 1,200 meters
into the air around 9:00 (0000 GMT) Friday, a local observatory
said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Japanese volcanologists of a Meteorological Agency
panel issued their first warning of possible high-speed
pyroclastic flows for the island since they started in late June
to announce volcanic activity around the mountain.
</P>
<P>
Mt. Oyama, which had erupted several times before, erupted
again on Tuesday, sending black smoke more than 5,000 meters high.
</P>
</TEXT>
