<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Seven Chinese cities, namely
Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan, Hohhot, Changsha, Chongqing, Guiyang and
Xining, reported slight air pollution today, with the highest
pollution reading at 164 in Taiyuan.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report released by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center, level two, or fairly good air
quality, was recorded in 28 other cities.
</P>
<P>
These cities are Beijing, Tianjin, Shenyang, Changchun, Harbin,
Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Hefei,
Nanchang, Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai, Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Guangzhou,
Shenzhen, Shantou, Nanning, Chengdu, Kunming, Xi'an, Lanzhou,
Yinchuan and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulates less than 10 microns in size were the major
pollutants in most of these cities, except Nantong, Changsha,
Chongqing and Guiyang, where sulfur dioxide was the major air
pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Seven cities -- Dalian, Fuzhou, Xiamen, Zhuhai, Zhanjiang,
Haikou and Lhasa -- reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level one or excellent (pollution reading: not
exceeding 50), level two or fairly good (pollution reading: 51 to
100), level three or slightly polluted (pollution reading: 101 to
200), level four or poor (pollution reading: 201 to 300), and
level five or hazardous (pollution reading: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored by the center include the four
municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing,
provincial capitals and major cities in the economically developed
coastal areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
