<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Says "No" to Uniting Armed Forces with Aussie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
says "No" to a proposal calling for merging the New Zealand
defense forces with their Australian counterparts.
</P>
<P>
A spokesperson for New Zealand Minister of Defense Mark Burton
said here Friday that while New Zealand's closest defense
relationship is with Australia, a united force is not something
the government has given thought to.
</P>
<P>
The remarks of the spokesperson are a response to a suggestion
raised earlier Friday by Australian National Party Senator Sandy
MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
While making a speech to the Australian Senate, MacDonald
suggested a joint ANZAC (Australian and New Zealand Army Corps)
force would make sense considering existing levels of cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
For all practical circumstances, he added, the two defense
forces are already integrated, but without acknowledgment and
planning.
</P>
<P>
MacDonald also extended the union idea to currency, saying such
things would come in a global world so they should start earlier
on a regional basis.
</P>
<P>
Senator MacDonald chairs Australia's Senate foreign affairs,
defense and trade legislation committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
