<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Review of Fijian Constitution Opposed in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand Council of
Trade Unions (NZCTU) opposes the announcement of a constitutional
review committee by the Great Council of Chiefs in Fiji, according
to a press release issued by NZCTU here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference of the South Pacific Organization of
Councils of Trade Unions (SPOCTU), which was held Friday in
Auckland, the biggest city in New Zealand, NZCTU Secretary Paul
Goulter said the Fijian interim administration has no mandate to
review the 1997 Constitution.
</P>
<P>
"Any review should be undertaken by the elected Parliament
within the framework of the provisions of that Constitution," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Goulter said the NZCTU is calling on the New Zealand government
to oppose this action and to advise the interim government in Fiji
of this country's concern.
</P>
<P>
Also at SPOCTU, a conference of Pacific trade union leaders,
President of the Fijian Trade Union Council Felix Anthony said the
review committee is not representative of the Fijian community and
that the committee includes a number of individuals closely
aligned with coup leader George Speight.
</P>
<P>
"Neither the Great Council of Chiefs nor the interim
administration has any mandate to rewrite the Constitution," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Anthony noted the Great Council of Chiefs is an advisory body
and should not be regarded as a substitute for an elected
parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
