<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disaster-Relief Drills Held in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Disaster-relief drills were
conducted across Japan Friday, the Disaster Prevention Day which
evokes memories of the 1923 Great Kanto earthquake that killed 140,
000 people in Tokyo and adjoining cities.
</P>
<P>
Some 5.85 million Japanese people took part in the annual
exercises in 33 of the country's 47 prefectures, according to a
tally by the National Land Agency.
</P>
<P>
The drills this year project a greater sense of urgency in view
of volcano eruptions and earthquakes that have hit the Izu Islands,
south of Tokyo, over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
In Shizuoka Prefecture, southwest of Tokyo, exercises
simulating a major earthquake striking the Tokai region along the
Pacific coast of central Honshu began in Kosai and other
localities.
</P>
<P>
At 8:30 a.m. (local time), Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori
sounded a mock alarm for a major Kanto earthquake from his
official residence in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
All members of the Japanese cabinet took part in the drill and
attended a teleconference with Shizuoka Governor Yoshinobu
Ishikawa.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, meanwhile, some 7,100 service members of the Self-
Defense Forces were deployed to a main avenue of the Ginza
shopping district to practice rescuing people trapped inside
buildings and underground.
</P>
<P>
In Hiratsuka, Kanagawa Prefecture, local authorities staged
relief exercises based on a destructive, vertical-type earthquake
hitting the southern Kanto region.
</P>
<P>
Japan Railway officials said they conducted drills simulating
train stoppages resulting from earthquake damage to Tokaido
Shinkansen Line bullet-train services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Successfully Launches Resource Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China successfully put its
earth resource satellite, the ZY-2, into the orbit with a Chinese
Long-March 4-B rocket that blasted off at 11:25 am today from the
Taiyuan Launching Center in north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The satellite is designed to gather and transmit remote sensing
images and data, and can be used for territorial surveying, city
planning, crop yield assessment, disaster monitoring and space
scientific experiment.
</P>
<P>
The ZY-2 is China's second transmitting-type remote sensing
satellite, after the launching of the Sino-Brazilian jointly made
earth resource satellite last October.
</P>
<P>
The 45-meter-long Long-March 4-B carrier rocket is an upgraded
version of the Long-March 4-A.
</P>
<P>
The launch is the 62nd time that Long March carriers have been
used.
</P>
<P>
The rocket and satellite separated 12 minutes after the
blasting off of the rocket before the satellite came into the
orbit.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that the successful launching of the ZY-2 earth
resource satellite is expected to help push ahead China's economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The Taiyuan Launching Center has conducted 20 major satellite
missions in the past five years, all proving successful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
