<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Records Trade Surplus for 33 Months by July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia recorded a trade
surplus in July 2000, the 33rd consecutive month to do so, but
with a lower amount in comparison with that in the corresponding
month of 1999.
</P>
<P>
In July 2000, a trade surplus of 4 billion ringgit (1.05
billion U.S. dollars) was achieved against the 5.9 billion ringgit
(1.55 billion U.S. dollars) recorded in the same month a year ago,
according to the statistics released here Friday by the Statistics
Department.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in the month under review was achieved despite a
higher import growth of 28.4 percent against the 15.8 percent
increase in exports, the department said.
</P>
<P>
Total exports in July was valued at 32.7 billion ringgit (8.6
billion U.S. dollars) while imports amounted to 28.7 billion
ringgit (7.55 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months this year, Malaysia recorded a
trade surplus of 33 billion ringgit (8.68 billion U.S. dollars)
against a surplus of 39.6 billion ringgit (10.42 billion U.S.
dollars) in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Both exports and imports registered a strong growth of 18.9
percent and 29.2 percent respectively with total exports amounting
to 208.5 billion ringgit (54.86 billion U.S. dollars) and imports
to 175.5 billion ringgit (46.18 billion U.S. dollars) during the
period under review. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
