<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Export Up in First Eight Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam registered an export
turnover of more than 9.2 billion U.S. dollars in the first eight
months of this year, a year-on-year increase of 27.4 percent,
according to Vietnam News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The country's state-owned sector contributed 4.85 billion U.S.
dollars, a 7.8 percent year-on-year increase, and the foreign-
invested sector, 4.35 billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 59.8
percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In August alone, Vietnam earned a record export turnover of 1.
34 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil remained the country's top export item in the past
eight months with an export volume of more than 10 million tons
and an export turnover of 2.2 billion U.S. dollars, a year-on-year
increase of 94.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other export items recording high increases in turnover
included garments with 1.17 billion U.S. dollars; footwear, 994
million U.S.dollars; seafood, 818 million U.S. dollars; electronic
appliances and computers, 496 million U.S. dollars; coffee, 353
million U.S. dollars; art and handicrafts, 171 million U.S.
dollars; pepper, 134 million U.S. dollars; and vegetables and
fruit, 115 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country exported 400,000 tons of rice in August, bringing
eight-month rice export volume to 2.35 million tons worth 473
million U.S. dollars, equaling 63 percent and 60 percent of the
same period last year respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country imported 9.737 billion U.S. dollars
worth of goods in the first eight months of 2000, an increase of
34.2 percent year-on-year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
