<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Major Parties Start to Hand in Nomination Lists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- With three more days for
nomination deadline, all major political parties of Sri Lanka
start on Friday to hand in their nomination lists for the upcoming
general elections and a rush in the next few days is expected.
</P>
<P>
However, Elections Commissioner Dayananda Dissanayake said he
was prepared to meet an expected rush from Friday onwards. Both
the ruling People's Alliance (PA) and the main opposition United
National Party (UNP), who will be in the forefront of the fray
will hand over their nomination lists from Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Elections Commissioner will meet representatives of
political parties next Tuesday to discuss arrangements for the
elections scheduled on October 10. Among matters to be discussed
will be the deployment of election monitors and arrangements to
ensure free and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
Three representatives from each party will be sent to meetings
which will be held every Friday until the conclusion of the
elections.
</P>
<P>
Returning Officers of the electoral districts will also be
meeting representatives of political parties on a district basis
during the run-up to the election to sort out any problems that
may arise.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the police too are preparing to ensure security for
the election. The head of the police election secretariat, Deputy
Inspector General A. A. Samarasinghe said that 35,000 policemen
will be deployed for election duty.
</P>
<P>
Road blocks will be set up to check on vehicles carrying
firearms and mobile and foot patrols will be conducted to ward off
possible incidents.
</P>
<P>
The Inspector General of Police Lucky Kodituwakku has ordered
all police personnel to maintain law and order and bring to book
any person violating the law no matter what his position is.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's 45 recognized political parties and a number of
independent groups have indicated that they will contest the
general elections. There are altogether 22 electoral districts
islandwide.
</P>
<P>
Some 12 million eligible voters are to cast their ballots at
more than 10,000 polling booths to choose 225 members to the next
parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
