<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Navy Builds Attack Craft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan navy has
constructed an attack craft for the first time at a cost of 7
million rupees (around 89,200 U.S. dollars) within a period of six
months.
</P>
<P>
A similar imported attack craft will cost 17 million rupees (
around 216,600 U.S. dollars), said Navy Commander Vice Admiral
Ciciel Tissera at a ceremony marking the official launching of the
craft at the Naval headquarters here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Commander complimented the engineers and other technical
staff who were engaged in the building of the craft.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Anurudha Ratwatte said that Sri Lanka
was an island country and the navy will take every possible action
to safeguard it. Nine more such craft were to be built and it was
a pleasure to supply all the raw material required for the purpose,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka with a coastal belt of 1,585 kilometers is vulnerable
in its north and east where the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (
LTTE) have been waging a 17 year bloody war against government
forces for a separate Tamil state.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE reportedly has a strong naval fleet manned by the Sea
Tigers who have repulsed the government naval force in the course
of several encounters. They have also successfully sunk three
naval vessels in the northern seas of the country in recent years.
</P>
