<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Reach Highest Level in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Boosted by strong global
demand, Thai exports reached 6 billion U.S. dollars in July, the
highest monthly level traced back to 1993, the Bank of Thailand (
BOT), the central bank, said in a report here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 22.7% expansion of July exports from the same period of
last year was better than the central bank's expectations, given
the decline trend of exports in the second quarter this year, it
noted.
</P>
<P>
Exported products posting strong gains in July included fishery
products, integrated circuits, electronic appliances, and plastics.
</P>
<P>
While stronger economic recovery in Asia and other major
overseas markets created huge demands for Thai goods, the weaker
baht, Thai currency, also helped enhance the competitiveness of
Thai products around the world, it said.
</P>
<P>
It believed that the improved export trend would help offset
the fragile recovery in domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Imports totaled 5.35 billion U.S. dollars in July, resulting in
an overall trade surplus of 650 million dollars, and the current
account surplus was 1.09 billion dollars, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
