<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Warns Against International Pressure Over E. Timor Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
warned the international community against pressuring Jakarta to
compromise over human rights abuses in East Timor, and against
pushing the government to implement the principle of retroactivity
because it could backfire.
</P>
<P>
"The government will not bow to international pressure to
compromise over human rights abuses in East Timor," Justice and
Human Rights Minister Yusril Ihza Mahendra was quoted by the
Indonesian Observer Friday as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I have to remind the international community that we could
also demand the Dutch and the Japanese governments (compensate)
for (past) war crimes committed during the independence war and
their periods of occupation here," he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said he had aired the warning during a meeting
with visiting members of the European parliament early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said they had asked him whether or not a recently amended
article in the Constitution would bar the government from trying
those held responsible for the violence in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the People's Consultative Assembly amended the 1945
Constitution to prevent an individual from being prosecuted under
laws that did not exist when a crime was committed. The amendment
has sparked intense debate over whether trials of East Timor human
rights abuses can go ahead as planned.
</P>
<P>
"I delivered this warning to members of the European parliament
earlier this morning (Thursday morning): 'that the international
community, specifically the western community, should not continue
pushing us to implement the retroactive principle because it can
backfire,'" he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahendra also said that an article in the same constitutional
amendment mentions that all citizens have to respect the limits
imposed by the laws, and as such the retroactive principle could
be applied to specific cases.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, I would like to convey to the international
community, that there should not be any fear of the amended
Article 28 of the Constitution," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian military was accused of killing thousands of
people in East Timor before or after a direct ballot which led to
the breakaway of East Timor from Indonesia last year.
</P>
<P>
The Attorney General had promised to announce 30 names as
suspects in the East Timor case. The case dossiers will then be
submitted to the court for further legal action.
</P>
<P>
Of 33 alleged suspects according to an earlier report by an
inquiry team established by the National Commission on Human
Rights, two are four-star generals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Logging Damages a Lot of Forests to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Illegal logging has damaged
400,000 to 800,000 hectares of forests annually to Indonesia, a
senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Log production from illegal logging averages 17 to 30 million
cubic meters every year in Indonesia, the Business News bulletin
Friday quoted Junior Minister for Forest Nurmahmudi Ismail as
saying.
</P>
<P>
A non-government organization has even reported that log
production from illegal logging has reached 52 percent of the
total wood production from natural forests in the country.
</P>
<P>
The degradation of forest land has reached about 1.6 million
hectares of forests annually in the past ten years, and
deforestation in 2000 is estimated to cover about 2.6 million
hectares of forest land, said the minister recently at a workshop
on illegal logging here.
</P>
<P>
The report said the national wood industry has the potential to
absorb the supply of 80 million cubic meters of logs annually
while natural forests in the country can supply only about 19.5
million cubic meters of logs annually. The shortage of log supply
has stimulated illegal logging.
</P>
<P>
Thus the domestic demand for logs actually has exceeded the
tolerable logging on natural forests. Therefore, the minister
emphasized the need to take concrete steps to ensure the
conservation of natural forests.
</P>
<P>
Tropical forests in Indonesia are one of the biodiversity
centers. Indonesia ranks the third among the seven
megabiodiversity countries in the world today.
</P>
<P>
Nurmahmudi conceded that illegal logging has threatened the
flora and fauna conservation in Indonesia. The government has
provided about 19 million hectares of forest land or about 13
percent of the total forests in the country for the forest
conservation purpose, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Indian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
