<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldova in Desperate Need of Elementary School Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Moldova is in desperate need
of primary and middle school teachers, and many schools have to
start the new term in September understaffed, news reports from
Chisinau claim.
</P>
<P>
In Moldova, at least 1,500 primary and middle school teaching
positions, mostly in math, English and biology, are unfilled
nationwide, a Ministry of Education and Science official said.
</P>
<P>
The situation in rural areas is worse than in the cities.
</P>
<P>
According to another education official, in the past three
years, about 8,000 elementary school teachers quit their jobs and
have gone to teach in colleges and universities, or to work in
other sectors.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that in the capital city of Chisinau,
from 1994 to 2000, a total of 7,000 normal college students
dropped out or changed their major.
</P>
<P>
Low pay and poor treatment are the main reasons for the
declining number of teachers in Moldovan schools.
</P>
<P>
A teachers' union in the capital revealed that a young
teacher's income in a month can meet only 15 percent of his
expenses, while a senior teacher who has been teaching for 18
years, can meet only 21.6 percent of his needs. To make ends meet,
they have to find several part-time jobs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
