<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Denies Involvement in Weapons Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Peru's Foreign Minister Fernando De
Trazegnies on Thursday once again denied that Peru's army was
involved in smuggling weapons from Jordan to Colombian rebels.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister claims the Jordanian government was
reportedly duped by international traffickers in arms.
</P>
<P>
"I have the impression that Jordan's government has been
surprised by a delinquent gang and that it trusted them in good
faith," said the FM, in defense of his government, which has
been named by Jordan as the buyer of weapons that were delivered
to Colombian guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Peru's Foreign Minister also rejected Jordanian charges that
Peruvian Air Force military aircraft were involved in the
transportation of the weapons.
</P>
<P>
Peru announced last week that it has smashed a ring that flew
10,000 Kalashnikov rifles from Jordan to Colombian rebels, which
has lead to a diplomatic flap between Peru and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government insists that the guns were sold
legally to Peru in 1998, but Peruvian government officials said
they never purchased the guns.
</P>
<P>
Jordan contends that a Peruvian General Lucio Olivera purchased
the rifles and made arrangements to have them shipped to Colombia
via the Amazon River and jungle, where the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia operate.
</P>
<P>
Peru however claims the alleged general involved in the
purchase and smuggling does not exist, said De Trazegnies.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian FM also advised that the purchase of said weapons
was canceled and the cancellation can be documented by Peruvian
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian government has sent a note to Jordan and is
waiting for an answer, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
