<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mountain Leprosy Outbreak Occurs in Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan health authorities
have raised an alert after an outbreak of "mountain leprosy" was
detected in Nueva Guinea, southeast Nicaragua, the Ministry of
Health reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that 422 cases of the disease have been found.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry is taking measures to control and prevent
the illness from spreading, since "mountain leprosy" could
reportedly affect more than 1,000 people in the region.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the treatment will not be started until
diagnosis is confirmed.
</P>
<P>
"Mountain leprosy" is transmitted by the bite of a mosquito
that lives in mountains and feeds on the blood of animals and
humans.
</P>
<P>
The incubation period for this sickness is three months.
Symptoms appear as skin ulcers and affects mucus membranes in the
nose, mouth and ears of victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
