<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 00300 GMT, September 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS -- Nigeria and its neighboring Equatorial Guinea have
reached an agreement on the delimitation of their long-disputed
maritime boundary, the News Agency of Nigeria reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Foreign Ministry hailed the agreement as opening a
new chapter in bilateral relations and said in a statement that
the agreement is to end the 10-year-long negotiations between the
two countries on a disputed maritime boundary spanning on oil-rich
waters. (Nigeria-Equitorial Guinea-Boundary)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece has decided to send more soldiers to the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo in order to increase the strength of
the Greek military contingent serving in the region.
</P>
<P>
Confirming this at a press briefing Thursday, Greek government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas said that Greece will send another
infantry unit to Kosovo. (Greece-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Sierra Leonean rebel group, The West Side Boys, which
is currently holding seven hostages, has put forward new demands
following the  earlier release of five of its captives, according
to reports reaching here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the rebel group Colonel Cambodia was quoted as
saying in Freetown, the capital of the war-torn west African
country, that the rebels wanted a review of the Lome Peace Accord,
their reintegration into the government army as well as the
release of their supporters from jail. (S.Leone-Rebels-Hostage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Cuba has agreed to resume suspended talks on
migration with the United States, the State Department said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The Cubans have informed us that they are now prepared to
resume these immigration talks," said State Department spokesman
Richard Boucher.
</P>
<P>
Boucher said that Cuba's decision to restart the talks,
suspended three months ago, was conveyed to Washington in a 15-
page diplomatic note delivered to the State Department late
Wednesday. (US-Cuba-Migration)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Thursday ruled out mediation
by a third party to help release a U.S. hostage held by Muslim
rebels in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"We're not interested in third-party mediation, we're not
seeking mediation efforts by third countries," State Department
Richard Boucher said, responding to a question that whether the U.
S. accepts the help offered by Libya. (US-Hostage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. armed forces are mostly ready to perform
wartime missions, but if the country had to fight two major wars
at the same time, it would run a high risk of increased casualties
because of shortfalls in logistic support, the Pentagon said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Most major combat and support forces are ready to meet
assigned taskings under this scenario (two wars at the same time),
although there are force readiness and capability shortfalls that
increase risk in executing operations," the Pentagon said in a
periodical assessment report to the Congress. (US-Pentagon)
</P>
</TEXT>
