<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> College Students To Get More Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- More loans are expected to be
provided for poor college students from this autumn, said sources
from the Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
Student loans were tried last year and proven to be effective
in cities with a high density of universities, including Beijing,
Shanghai and other six cities.
</P>
<P>
The education loans for students from poor families is a major
step for implementing the government strategy of reinvigorating
the nation through science, technology and education.
</P>
<P>
It also helps improve the development of China's educational
sector and deepen the reform of the education system, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
To inform cash-strapped students about how to apply for loans,
the ministry circulated booklets in June to those sitting the
national college entrance exams.
</P>
<P>
The booklets explain the State's policies and the assistance it
offers to poor students.
</P>
<P>
Specific departments and individuals will be appointed by
schools to establish links with regional banks to supply loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Welcomes Election of New Somali President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government Friday
welcomed the election of Abdiqasim Salad Hassan as President of
Somalia and reiterated its full support for the new president and
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"As a country, we welcome the election of interim Somali
President Mr. Hassan," Foreign Minister Bonaya Godana told a press
conference here Friday.
</P>
<P>
But Godana said that viable peace in Somalia can only be
achieved through inclusion of faction leaders.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the warlords and other faction leaders who stay out to
show their goodwill and come onboard," said the foreign minister,
adding: "We hope the international community will do the same and
we are looking forward to seeing a functional government and
functional state."
</P>
<P>
"We are still exacting our own diplomatic pressure and offering
advice that the new team should go out of its way to bring in the
warlords," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, which shares a 1,200-kilometer border with the war-torn
Somalia, is home to 200,000 Somali refugees.
</P>
<P>
When and whether to repatriate the Somali refugees will be
determined by the assessment of the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees and Kenya will fully cooperate with the
agency, Godana said.
</P>
<P>
Somalia plunged into a civil war in 1991 and has had no central
government since then.
</P>
<P>
A peace conference aimed at ending Somalia's anarchy has been
underway since May 2 in Djibouti. A central government in Somalia
is to be set up in the coming days following the presidential
election on August 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Tries to Put out Forest Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- South African fire
fighters battled on Friday afternoon a blaze raging through a pine
and gum plantation in Sabie of Mpumalanga Province beginning from
Thursday afternoon, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
South African Forestry Company Limited (Safcol) engineering
manager Benno Krieg said the fire had destroyed thousands of trees
in its Bergvliet plantation.
</P>
<P>
He said Sabie's fire brigade and the community were trying to
put out the fire, saying that the fire did not pose a threat to
communities as the plantation was not near any residential areas.
</P>
<P>
Krieg said they hoped to extinguish the fire late Friday. But
he said it would depend on the weather.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Water Affairs and Forestry in Mpumalanga has
banned people in terms of the Forestry Act from making fires in
the open until October 31, when the worst of the dry season is
over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
