<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Study Notes Rapid Rise of Internet Use Outside of U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Internet use outside the
United States may be rising much faster than predicted just last
year, according to a report released Friday by an American
industry-funded public policy group.
</P>
<P>
The report from the United States Internet Council (USIC)
estimates that 304 million people worldwide used the Internet on a
regular basis as of March 2000, most of them from outside North
America.
</P>
<P>
There were fewer than 90,000 Internet users just seven years
ago, and 171 million in 1999. Current predictions indicate that
Internet users could exceed the 1 billion mark by 2005, with 700
million located outside North America, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"Over the last decade U.S. users and English language content
have defined the Internet as a U.S.-centric environment," the
report said. "However, as more users come online in Europe and
Asia as well as the rest of the world, the Internet is becoming
multicultural, multilingual and multipolar."
</P>
<P>
According to the USIC, English is losing its dominant position
on the World Wide Web in favor of increased linguistic diversity.
Currently, only just over 50 percent of all Internet users are
native English speakers.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the report said, English-language Web sites continue to
dominate. Seventy-eight percent of all websites and 96 percent of
e-commerce sites are currently in English. Additionally, 70
percent of all websites originate in the U.S. and the vast
majority of them are in English. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
