<DOCNO> XIE20000901.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Seen to Have Great Potential in Internet Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Asia-Pacific as a whole
seems set to play a dynamic role in future Internet development, a
U.S. group tracking the online world said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The region is the third of rapid Internet growth, after North
America and Europe, currently boasting approximately 70 million
Internet users, said the United States Internet Council (USIC), an
industry-funded public policy group.
</P>
<P>
Internet users in Asia-Pacific now account for 23 percent of
the worldwide total of 304 million. The USIC said that the region,
representing almost half the world's population, has significant
growth potential.
</P>
<P>
Regional growth forecasts estimate that by 2003 Asian users
will surpass North American and European users and exceed 200
million. By 2004, Asia-Pacific e-commerce should reach 1.6
trillion U.S. dollars and account for almost 20 percent of the
global total, according to the USIC report.
</P>
<P>
Japan, second only to the U.S. in terms of Internet use, leads
the region. Its total number of Internet users has soared from
around 17 million in 1999 to 27 million in 2000, and is expected
to approach 77 million by 2005..
</P>
<P>
The USIC said that China has the potential to surpass Japan as
the region's dominant Internet nation. Although Internet
penetration remains low, the country has already risen to second
place, behind Japan, in terms of users, with 12.3 million users
online, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
