<HEADLINE> Gore Intensifies Campaign Around Labor Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore will intensify his campaign around
Labor Day, which marks the traditional opening of the fall
campaign season.
</P>
<P>
Gore's itinerary around Labor Day includes stops at an all-
night diner, a fire station, a parade and a speedway rally.
</P>
<P>
He will begin the Labor Day blitz Sunday with a meeting with
construction workers in Philadelphia. From there, Gore will head
for Michigan to meet with hospital workers.
</P>
<P>
Then Gore will fly to Tampa, Florida, to chat with voters at an
all-night diner and bakery, before breakfast at dawn with
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
Gore will join union workers in Pittsburgh to mark Labor Day
Monday, then head to Louisville, Kentucky, to wrap up his marathon
with an evening rally outside a motor speedway.
</P>
<P>
"Labor day begins a two-month home stretch for the campaign,"
Gore said Friday. "I'm looking forward to it."
</P>
<P>
History shows that the presidential candidate significantly
ahead in the polls around Labor Day has won every election for the
last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
A Newsweek poll released Friday showed Gore 10 points ahead of
his Republican rival George W. Bush and other polls out late next
week will give further evidence whether or not Gore is gaining a
lead.
</P>
<P>
The Republicans launched a new TV ad Friday in 17 states
questioning Gore's credibility, with an image of his appearance at
a fund-raising affair at a Buddhist temple in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Texas Governor Bush claimed Friday that his Republican
presidential campaign was "in excellent shape."
</P>
<P>
He said that he had the momentum against Al Gore despite
distractions and slipping polls.
</P>
<P>
Bush was campaigning Friday in Arkansas, concentrating on the
education issue that has been his chosen topic during the week of
campaign.
</P>
<P>
His aide said Bush will campaign more aggressively after Labor
Day. 
</P>
