<HEADLINE> IMF Forecasts Italy's Economic Growth in 2000 at 3.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund (
IMF) Friday revised upwards its April forecasts for Italy's
economic growth this year and next.
</P>
<P>
The new forecasts are 3.1 percent in 2000 (compared to April's
2.7 percent forecast) and 3.0 percent in 2001 (compared to 2.8
percent).
</P>
<P>
The new forecasts are contained in the IMF's World Economic
Outlook to be presented at its annual meeting in Prague in
September, the Italian news agency Ansa reported.
</P>
<P>
The IMF forecasts are more optimistic than the latest ones from
the Italian government, contained in its three-year economic plan -
- 2.8 percent in 2000 and 2.9 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The forecasts may still be slightly altered, but the picture is
clear: after years of slow growth, Italy is close to hitching its
economic convoy to the European train, which is showing sharp
growth.
</P>
<P>
According to the preliminary copy of the report, the IMF is set
to revise upwards its forecasts for the euro zone, with 3.4
percent growth in 2000 and 2001, compared to 3.2 percent for both
years predicted in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
