<HEADLINE> S. American Presidents Defend Regional Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- South America's competitivity
in the world economy depends on a better integration between the
economic blocs of the continent, the 12 presidents said Friday in
the Communique of Brasilia, issued at the end of the first South
American Summit.
</P>
<P>
The Southern Common Market (Mercosur) and the Community of
Andean Nations (CAN) chiefs of state decided to start talks to
create a free trade area between the two blocs before January 2002.
</P>
<P>
The presidents also supported the Plan of Action for the
Creation of the Regional Infrastructure in South America, a study
made by the Interamerican Development Bank (IDB). "The presidents
regard as being of priority the identification of work of
bilateral and subregional interest," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of the 12 countries of the continent reaffirmed
their commitment toward the perfecting of the multilateral system
of commerce, said the document.
</P>
<P>
It also stressed the concern of the presidents for the
imbalances in the international financial markets.
</P>
<P>
According to the text, the presidents want the international
financial community to work to find a rapid solution to that
problem to recover the economic growth of the continent.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori said he hoped the accord
would represent a first step toward eventual creation of "the
United States of South America" though he conceded this may be
little more than wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
Chilean President Ricardo Lagos, for his part, said the
agreement should eventually be extended to include Central America
and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
"From South America, we have to look at the whole of Latin
America because that's where we will have to eventually have a
complete integration process," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
