<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Move Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks moved
higher Friday after the latest reports showed more signs that the
U.S. economy is slowing and inflation remains tame.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 23.68 at 11,238.78
points, extending its gain of 112.09 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 27.98 at 4,243.33 and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 3.09 at 1,520.77.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported that the unemployment rate
increased to 4.1 percent in August from 4.0 percent in July while
the National Association of Purchasing Management said U.S.
manufacturing activity shrank in August for the first time in 19
months.
</P>
<P>
The reports offered further proof that the U.S. economy is
slowing and inflation remains under control, which would prompt
the Federal Reserve to end the current cycle of monetary
tightening policy.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised rates for six times in the past
14 months in an effort to cool off the economy and prevent
inflation from rising. The central bank decided to leave rates
unchanged at a monetary policy meeting last week but hold the door
open to a further rate hike if a threat to inflation arises.
</P>
<P>
The Dow index was pushed higher by its components of IBM and
Hewlett-Packard even as brokerage and bank shares fell after a
rally in the previous sessions.
</P>
<P>
Big technology names such as Oracle led the Nasdaq composite's
advance. Yahoo! fell after bearish comments on a falloff in its
adverting revenue.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 3.05 at 677.58 and the American Stock
Exchange index was up 12.30 at 955.78. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 4.02 at 541.91.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,647 up, 1,195 down and 502
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 766.47 million shares from 1.05 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
